<HEADLINE> Sudanese Opposition Committed to Egyptian-Libyan Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Sudanese opposition alliance on
Monday reiterated its endorsement of and commitment to an Egyptian-
Libyan initiative aimed at helping realize peace in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The National Democratic Alliance (NDA) stressed its stance on
Sudan's reconciliation process in a statement released after a
meeting held in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
NDA groups Sudan's northern Muslim opposition parties, which
want to share power with the government, and the Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), which has been fighting a 17-year war with
the government for greater autonomy for the mostly Christian and
animist-populated southern states.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance supports a call, included in the
Egyptian-Libyan initiative, for a peace conference between the
Sudanese government and the opposition to seek national
reconciliation, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Libya proposed last year a five-point peace plan,
calling for a permanent ceasefire between the Sudanese government
and the SPLA, besides the peace gathering.
</P>
<P>
The NDA leadership appreciated Egypt's efforts to coordinate
with the Eastern African Inter-Governmental Authority for
Development (IGAD) on mediating peace in Sudan, the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, IGAD has sponsored several rounds of talks between
the Sudanese government and the SPLA. But little tangible
achievement has been made so far.
</P>
<P>
The NDA appealed to Al-Sadeq Al-Mahdi, former Sudanese prime
minister and leader of the Ummah Party, to rejoin the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Al-Mahdi, formerly a key leader of the opposition, broke away
from the alliance after signing a peace agreement with the
government in November 1999.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been keen on mediating between the Sudanese government
and the opposition in a bid to safeguard the territorial integrity
of its southern neighbor, for fear that a possible disintegration
of Sudan may jeopardize its major water source, the Nile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
