<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Monday
voiced alarm about its besieged peacekeepers in Sierra Leone,
saying they only had 10 days of supplies left and floods make it
impossible to bring in more goods.
</P>
<P>
Some 222 Indian peacekeepers and 11 unarmed U.N. military
observers have been surrounded for two months by the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) in their stronghold Kailahun,
some 320 kilometers east of the nation's capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
"The effective re-supply of the U.N. mission contingent has
not been possible for a considerably amount of time. They now have
10 days worth of rations left," spokesman Marie Okabe said on
behalf of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who is in Togo to
attend the summit of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
She said that rains have flooded roads, making it nearly
impossible for vehicles to reach the area. On Friday, the rebels
refused to allow a helicopter bringing supplies to land.
</P>
<P>
"So there was an escalation of obstacles in trying to re-supply
them," Okabe said. "We are taking the situation very seriously and
every effort is made to re-supply them by every possible means."
</P>
<P>
Okabe also said a large arms cache was found in the Lungi area
in the north but she had no further details.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Annan asked Liberia, whose leader is close with
rebel leader Foday Sankoh, to help gain the release of encircled U.
N. soldiers, saying he was "extremely concerned" about the troops.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, who is in currently the government custody, violated
the Lome peace accord signed in July last year, and the RUF
fighters took U.N. soldiers hostage, and disarm them as they are
in the West African country to monitor the peace accord. 
</P>
