<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Handshake May Provide More Information to Others Than You Think </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A new study backed up what the
etiquette books have been saying all along, that a firm handshake
helps make a good first impression for both males and females.
</P>
<P>
The University of Alabama study, led by psychologist William F.
Chaplin, involved 112 men and women in college. The students
completed four personality questionnaires and shook hands twice
with four handshake coders who had a month of training and
practice in shaking hands and evaluating handshakes.
</P>
<P>
Before the handshaking, the students did not know their
handshakes were being evaluated however.
</P>
<P>
Those with a firm handshake were more extroverted and open to
experience and less neurotic and shy than those with a less firm
or limp handshake, Chaplin and his colleagues said in the July
issue of the Journal of Personality and Social Psychology.
</P>
<P>
Men tended to have firmer handshakes than women. And women who
are more liberal, intellectual and open to new experiences had a
firmer handshake and make a more favorable impression than those
who were less open and had a less firm handshake.
</P>
<P>
"We did find that handshakes are stable and consistent across
time and gender," the researchers wrote. "Given What we know about
the potency of first impressions, it might be a good idea to heed
the recommendations of experts...and try to make that first
handshake a firm one." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
