<HEADLINE> Barak Survives Knesset Vote, Leaves for Camp David Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
left here on Monday for the Ben Gurion International airport on his
way to the Camp David summit due to begin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Barak has just survived a no-confidence vote aimed at toppling
his government and thwarting his efforts to conduct crucial
negotiations with the Palestinians in the United States-sponsored
three-way summit.
</P>
<P>
In the summit with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S.
President Bill Clinton, Barak will try to hammer out a framework
deal with the Palestinians for the settlement of such thorny issues
as the status of Jerusalem, the future of Jewish settlements,
borders, water resources and the fate of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The motions against Barak's government was voted 54 for, 52
against, with seven abstentions. Although the opposition failed to
rally 61 votes required in the 120-seat parliament to bring down
the government, the result of the vote showed Barak's lack of a
majority support in the Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
This fact, together with his shaky 42-seat minority coalition
government following the defection of three right-wing parties,
increased doubts about the prime minister's ability to make fateful
decisions and decisive compromises that the upcoming negotiations
will require. 
</P>
</TEXT>
