<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Court Issues Arrest Warrant Against Fugitive Spy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian court issued arrest
warrant on Monday against Eshaq Belanas, an Iranian Jew suspected
spy and who was said to have fled the country in 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to Hussein Ali Amiri, head of justice of Iran's
southern Fars Province, the fugitive was head of a spy network
working for Israel and is currently in the United States, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iran will seek arrest of the fugitive through the International
Police (Interpol), the official said. However, he did not say
whether the Interpol had agreed to cooperate in the action.
</P>
<P>
A court in Shiraz, capital of Fars, had tried 17 Iranian
nationals for spying for Israel, including 13 Jews and four
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Twelve of the defendants, two Muslims and 10 Jews, got prison
terms of between two and 13 years, while the other five were
acquitted, according to a verdict issued on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Amiri said the spy case will remain open until all those
involved in spying for Israel are brought to justice. He added,
however, that the court will not make public the list of fugitive
suspects for the time being for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Since the arrest of the Jews early last year, Iran has been
under severe pressure from Western countries to release them.
Israel has denied that the Iranian Jews had worked for its secret
service.
</P>
<P>
After the court verdict on July 1, Western countries stepped up
their criticism and pressed Iran to overturn the sentences. Iran,
however, insists that the trial and verdict were rational and fair
and no foreign country should meddle in Iran's internal affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Fighting Survival at Home Prior to Camp David Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
is fighting in the parliament on Monday for the survival of his
ruling coalition in a vote on no-confidence motions before he sets
out for the three-way Camp David summit in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Barak's way to the Camp David summit has been tough since he
tried in vain to keep three rebellious right-wing ruling partners
in his coalition.
</P>
<P>
The 120-member Knesset (parliament) is having a heated debate on
two no-confidence motions. One submitted last week by the
opposition Likud party against "Barak's concessions and
capitulations to (Palestinian leader Yasser) Arafat even before the
summit".
</P>
<P>
The other one was concerning the doctors' strike which has been
going on for four months. The two motions are expected to be put to
a simultaneous vote.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, bolstered by the 26 Knesset members from the
three parties that quit the government on Sunday, is going all out
in a bid to muster 61 votes necessary to topple the government.
</P>
<P>
Barak joined the debate to defend his positions on the peace
talks with the Palestinians after returning from a meeting with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Cairo. He delayed his departure
for the United States so that he could be in the Knesset to deal
with the motions.
</P>
<P>
The grave-looking prime minister found his speech frequently
interrupted by the disagreeing voices. He put off the departure so
that he and Transport Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak from Center
Party, who is in the Israeli delegation for the summit, can cast a
vote.
</P>
<P>
Barak reiterated his "red lines" on the negotiations with the
Palestinians: no return to the 1967 lines, a united Jerusalem under
Israeli sovereignty, no foreign army west of the Jordan River, a
majority of the Jewish residents of West Bank and Gaza will remain
in settlement blocs, and no Israeli recognition of legal or moral
responsibility for creating the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that he received the mandate from the people to
forge peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In emotional exposition of his stance, Barak said "I, as a
solider of 35 years, know the meaning of security and the pain of
loss of lives."
</P>
<P>
"Peace is the profound change in our life styles. ... Peace will
bring economic growth, employment, health and investment in
infrastructure.... equal opportunities for all," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said,"Israeli power will be maintained in the
future to ensure peace. Israel is proceeding toward peace because
it wants a peaceful future for the children."
</P>
<P>
The defection of the 17-seat ultra-Orthodox Shas Party, the
four-seat Yisrael Ba'aliya and the five-seat National Religious
Party leaves Barak with a coalition of only one-third seats of the
Knesset.
</P>
<P>
However, he is expected to get support from the 10 Knesset
members form the Arab parties and the two members of the Democratic
Choice faction of Knesset Member Roman Bronfman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0035 </DOCNO>
