<HEADLINE> Algerian Trade Minister in Iraq for Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Algerian Minister of Commerce
Mourad Medelci arrived in the Iraqi capital Baghdad on Monday
evening to attend the Algerian-Iraqi Joint Committee meetings, the
official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The meetings will tackle the issue of promoting bilateral
cooperation in all fields, said INA.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Medelci is expected to hold talks with senior
Iraqi officials and sign contracts with the Iraqi side within the
framework of the United Nations oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Algeria has signed contracts worth 70 million U.S. dollars
during the past seven phases of the U.N. oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. humanitarian deal, which started in 1996, allows Iraq
to sell a certain amount of oil in every six months to buy food,
medicine and other necessities to help offset the impacts of the
stringent U.N. sanctions imposed since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Algeria, as an Arab country, has been calling on the U.N. as
well as the Arab League to lift the decade-old sanctions and put an
end to the suffering of the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
