<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Misses OAU for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
failed to attend the annual Organization of African Unity (OAU)
summit which started in Togo on Monday, the first time since the
country won independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
It could not be immediately established why Mugabe did not
travel to Togo. According to presidential spokesman George
Charamba, Mugabe, who was being represented by his Foreign
Minister Stan Mudenge at the summit, could not travel because he
was busy forming his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted informed sources in
the Ministry of Foreign Affairs as saying that Mugabe was
boycotting the summit together with leaders of other African
countries who disliked Togo being the venue because Togo supported
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
rebels in Angola.
</P>
<P>
A recent study by the United Nations Security Council revealed
that countries such as Togo and Burkina Faso were breaching a U.N.
resolution of sanctions against UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Angola had mobilized some southern African countries to boycott
the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
