<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Trying to Get Free AIDS Drug for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is currently
negotiating with five pharmaceutical companies for reduced prices
on HIV/AIDS drugs in African countries, said Public Relations
Officer of Uganda AIDS Commission Anne Nagawasi here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Uganda Drug Initiative Program Manager Dorothy
Ochora, Uganda would want zero prices if possible, because it is a
poor developing country and can not afford the prices.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agencies involved in this endeavor include the UNAIDS,
the World Health Organization, the World Bank and the United
Nations Children's Fund. The drug companies involved are
Beohringer Ingelheim, Bristol-Myers Squibb, Glaxo Wellcome, Merck &AMP;
Co. Inc. and E Hoffman-la Roche.
</P>
<P>
So far only Glaxo Wellcome has publicly announced a reduction
in price of its Combivir, a kind of HIV/AIDS drug, from a global
average price of 16 dollars to two dollars in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
There are around one million Ugandans living with or dying from
HIV/AIDS. The average cost of treatment is about 600 dollars a
month, but many Ugandans live on less than one dollar a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
