<HEADLINE> Liberia Sends More Troops to Border With Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government has sent
reinforcements to its north-western border following an alleged
attack from neighboring Guinea, according to a report reaching
here from the Liberian capital Monrovia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a statement issued by Liberian Foreign
Ministry on Sunday as saying that the attack took place on
Saturday morning in Koryamah, a border town in northern Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"This brings to three the number of attacks emanating from the
Guinean territory," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have steadily grown between Liberia, Guinea and Sierra
Leone, which regularly accused each other of sponsoring attacks on
each other's territory.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the Liberian government is to "
issue a formal protest to the Guinean government, the Economic
Community of West African States and the United Nations about the
latest reported attack."
</P>
<P>
Liberia would do all it could to prevent the conflict from
spreading, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The former two attacks, which were launched in the same area by
unidentified insurgents from Guinea, took place in April and
August 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian government has recently accused a "massive influx"
of British weapons, "under the guise of arming the so-called
Sierra Leone government forces", of raising tensions in the West
African region. 
</P>
