<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Tourists Expected to Visit Zimbabwe: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Mines, Environment and
Tourism Minister Simon Moyo said here on Monday that the volume of
tourists to Zimbabwe is expected to improve after the
parliamentary election largely hailed as peaceful.
</P>
<P>
He told local reporters that the industry had suffered a
temporary setback because of negative publicity about Zimbabwe
abroad just before the country's biggest election since 1980.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of potential visitors were reluctant to come to
Zimbabwe because of the uncertainty of the political situation
just before the election held two weeks ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are still assessing how best we can improve the volume of
tourists to Zimbabwe, but we hope more people will start trickling
again to our beautiful country," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Moyo, his ministry would soon launch the Tourism
Recovery Plan to assure travelers in other countries that Zimbabwe
is a safe place to visit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chief Executive of Zimbabwe Council for Tourism
Elias Nyakunu said the industry is at its lowest because of the
crisis Zimbabwe has been passing through.
</P>
<P>
Between 60 to 70 percent of business has been lost because of
the fuel crisis which started in November last year largely
because of a shortage of foreign currency, he said, noting that
some businesses had temporarily closed in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Last year, about 1.2 million tourists visited Zimbabwe, earning
the country 157 million U.S. dollars in foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry is Zimbabwe's third biggest foreign
currency earner after agriculture and mining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
