<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Revisionist Theories Lambasted at AIDS Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Yu Dabo
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Many participants attending
the ongoing 13th International AIDS Conference in Durban, South
Africa on Monday attacked the revisionist theories that HIV does
not cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the first to be held in a developing country
and on the African continent, is being marked by a stronger chorus
of researchers and politicians alike who uphold the traditional
theory linking HIV with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The "revisionists" challenging the traditional theory are
dwarfed by a much larger number of "traditionalists", but the
dispute between the two schools of thoughts is believed to be
dragging efforts to find ways to rein in the rampant spread of
AIDS, particularly on the African continent, experts warned.
</P>
<P>
Some delegates argued that wasting too much time to dispute the
cause of AIDS would weaken the political will and leadership in
the fight against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
British scientist, professor Roy Anderson criticized the school
of dissident theorists, saying the basis of his research was
formulated on the premise that the HIV virus did in fact cause
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Without targeting certain government leaders by name, he said
the explosive spread of AIDS in Africa over the past 13 years
could have been curtailed if nipped in the bud, since it was
already known back in 1987 how to prevent the transmission of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he asserted that questioning whether HIV causes AIDS
would surely prevent certain governments from intervening timely
to curb the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"Actions taken now and early can help to dramatically reduce
the epidemic," Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
South African High Court judge Edwin Cameron, who stated
publicly that he is HIV-positive, told a plenary session that any
support for the revisionist theories would shake everyone engaged
in the combat against the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Any flirtation with dissidents would create disbelief and
confusion among scientists and AIDS workers alike, he said while
delivering a keynote address for the first Jonathan Mann Memorial
Lecture. Mann, who played a major role in conceiving and
constructing a global response to the AIDS pandemic, was killed in
a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
In the national struggle to come to grips with the epidemic,
perhaps the most intractably puzzling episode has been the
flirtation with those who in the face of all reason and evidence
have sought to dispute the etiology of AIDS, Cameron said,
referring to certain South African officials.
</P>
<P>
"This has shaken almost everyone responsible for engaging the
epidemic. It has created an air of unbelief amongst scientists,
confusion among those at risk of HIV and consternation amongst
AIDS workers," Cameron said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that with a population of 43 million, South Africa has
an estimated 4.2 million AIDS sufferers, one of the highest number
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Every month 5,000 HIV-positive babies were born in South Africa,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Their lives involve preventable infections, preventable
suffering, and preventable death. And if none of that is
persuasive, then from the point of view of the nation's economic
self-interest, their HIV infection entails preventable expense.
Yet we have done nothing," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Cameron, the true challenge for the AIDS
conference is to "make the future different". This includes the
provision of affordable drugs to the millions of people suffering
from the disease, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
