<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Official Refutes Criticism Over HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- South African Health Minister
Manto Tshabalala-Msimang Monday refuted criticism against her
government's stance on HIV/AIDS, saying her country would devise
its own health policies.
</P>
<P>
South Africa would not bend to pressure to conform to the
expectations of the industrialized world in regard to the fight
against AIDS, she told reporters while attending the 13th
International AIDS Conference in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"It's not that we don't care (about AIDS), but the
international community put pressure on us and very few support us
in getting on with our business of transformation," she said.
</P>
<P>
She emphasized the government's commitment to fighting AIDS,
reiterating that prevention and awareness is its primary goal over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The minister strongly defended President Thabo Mbeki, who has
been widely criticized for his interest in the debate between
revisionist "AIDS theorists who question whether the HIV virus
causes AIDS and scientists who link HIV with AIDS."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, when officially opening the conference Sunday night,
called on all parties to tolerate different viewpoints,
disappointing many orthodox scientists who had hoped Mbeki would
withdraw his defence of the so-called "dissident" scientists.
</P>
<P>
"The president of this country has never denied either the
existence of AIDS nor this causal connection between HIV and AIDS,
" Tshabalala-Msimang said.
</P>
<P>
"Why should he deny something he has not said? The media should
turn it around and report correctly," she said.
</P>
<P>
The issues surrounding the HIV/AIDS debate were complex and
multi-faceted, she added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the government's reported unavailability to meet
with pharmaceutical companies to negotiate deals to buy cheaper
drugs, Tshabalala-Msimang said, "to say we are unavailable to them
... I dismiss that outright."
</P>
<P>
She singled out the U.S.-based drug manufacturer Pfizer as one
of the drug companies which had made offers to provide drugs to
HIV sufferers at a reduced cost, without consulting the government.
</P>
<P>
"I was not informed about this. I did not even know the terms
of the offer," she said.
</P>
<P>
Tshabalala-Msimang, who chairs the health sector of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC), told another
briefing with four other SADC ministers, that SADC would develop a
drugs package which could be negotiated with multinational
pharmaceutical companies to suit the specific needs of SADC member
nations.
</P>
<P>
"This package will not focus only on the provision of anti-
retroviral drugs, but will address the issue of HIV-related
interventions in a holistic way ... including laboratory support,
treatment of opportunistic infections, infrastructure and capacity
building," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
