<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Probe Death of 13 Soccer Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's police Monday said a
board of inquiry has been put in place to establish the cause of
the National Sports Stadium stampede during a soccer match between
South Africa and Zimbabwe on Sunday, which killed 13 people.
</P>
<P>
"While there has already been finger pointing from various
quarters aimed at the police, the complexity of the situation and
intertwining events has led to the board of inquiry composed of
four senior officials being established," said Chief
Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena.
</P>
<P>
He said the board would look into issues which included the
role and actions of the police and the security situation at the
stadium in Harare on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The board would require written as well as oral evidence from
people who witnessed the tragedy, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let the nation be assured that nothing is going to be swept
under the carpet," he said. "Considering the urgency of the
situation, the findings and recommendations of the board should be
made public soon."
</P>
<P>
Police have been accused for causing the tragedy when they
fired teargas after few hooligans threw missiles into the football
pitch.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Human Rights Organization Monday condemned police
for using teargas on 55,000 soccer fans who were at the stadium on
Sunday, resulting in the deaths of 13 people.
</P>
<P>
Police could have dealt with the few hooligans without using
teargas and allowed the game to proceed, the organization said.
</P>
<P>
It said Zimbabwe was being rated as a violent country because
each time people gathered for entertainment armed police would be
deployed there.
</P>
<P>
"Teargas should never be brought to entertainment places. It is
high time people should refrain from such bad behavior," the
organization stressed.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe was beaten 0-2 by South Africa in the World Cup
qualifier tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
