<HEADLINE> French FM Disagrees With German Proposal on European Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said on Monday that he disagrees with the German foreign
minister's proposal to have a directly elected European president
in future.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily L'Humanite, Vedrine said that
the proposal made by German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer is ``
simple and seducing'' but does not correspond to the reality of
Europe today.
</P>
<P>
``We cannot copy the American model. I am not ready to follow
the logic according to which France and Germany would be like
Virginia and Massachusetts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that if a federal-style European president is entitled
to great power, the role of a French president and a German
chancellor would be put into question.
</P>
<P>
Fischer proposal on May 12 that Europe have a federal-style
union in future with a directly elected executive, a two-chamber
parliament and a constitution.
</P>
<P>
This proposal has caused a great controversy in the French
political circles. 
