<HEADLINE> Belgian FM Explains Arrest Warrant to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian foreign minister had
to explain to the country's parliament on Monday when and why
Belgium had issued an arrest warrant against a Congolese
government official.
</P>
<P>
Louis Michel told the parliamentary foreign affairs commission
that it was last week when his ministry notified the Congolese
foreign ministry about the issuance of the arrest warrant against
Congolese Foreign Minister Abdoulaye Yerodia.
</P>
<P>
The move not only caused bilateral rows but also internal
dispute in Belgium as well.
</P>
<P>
The African country has recalled its Brussels-based ambassador
to "consult with" the incident while two of the Belgian cabinet
officials had to call off their scheduled visits to the Congo, a
former colony of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Democratic Christian Party from the Flemish-
speaking half of Belgium labeled the incident as the start of a
political dispute domestically.
</P>
<P>
A fax document from the Belgian justice ministry confirmed that
Belgium had issued the arrest warrant on June 6, long before the
Belgian foreign minister's trip to the Congo at the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
The arrest warrant was only made known on July 3 after Michel
had returned from a ceremony on June 30 in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Belgium issued the arrest warrant against the Congolese foreign
minister on charges of crimes against humanity. The arrest
warrant was signed on April 11 by Brussels Magistrate Damien
Vandermeersh but was only issued almost a month later due to legal
and technical reasons, according to jurisdiciary explanations.
</P>
<P>
The Belgians made the move after Congolese refugees had accused
their foreign minister of inciting hatred against them in August
1998 in speeches using such discriminative words as "vermin" and"
extermination".
</P>
<P>
The arrest warrant was issued in line with a 1993 Belgian law
that demands arrest of those who have committed crimes against
international human rights no matter where they have committed the
crimes and what nationality they are of.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese foreign minister is now liable to arrest if he
enters Belgium or any other country that is willing to execute the
arrest warrant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
