<HEADLINE> Canada's JDS Closes Biggest Take-over Deal with U.S. Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada's JDS Uniphase Corp. closed
its ever biggest take-over deal with the U.S.-based SDL Inc. by
agreeing to pay 41 billion U.S. dollars in stock Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
JDS chief executive officer Jozef Straus said the agreement "
will help us accelerate the development of the next generation of
fibre-optic components that our customers need."
</P>
<P>
Officials with both companies believe the agreement could be
the biggest technology deal as well.
</P>
<P>
Under the take-over deal, JDS will exchange 3.8 shares of its
own stock for each share of SDL, which, based in San Hose,
California, is one of the few remaining fibre-optic component
manufacturers capable of challenging JDS's position as the world's
biggest in the field.
</P>
<P>
The deal, however, may have to come through the close scrutiny
by U.S. anti-trust regulators, who already imposed conditions on
their approval of JDS's deal with another U.S.-based firm E-Tek
Dynamics last month. 
</P>
