<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Egypt Open Conference on Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- In a further show of rapprochement,
Iranian and Egyptian experts opened a round-table conference here
on Monday to discuss ways of improving bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts and experts from both countries will discuss
bilateral ties, the situation in the Middle East and the foreign
policy of the two countries during the two-day conference held at
the Iranian Foreign Ministry's Institute for Political and
International Studies.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the conference, Abd Al-Menem, director of the
Egyptian Al-Ahram Center for Strategic Studies, said the
discussions are being held at a time when the ice in Tehran-Cairo
relations has thawed.
</P>
<P>
It is now the appropriate time for restoring relations between
the two nations after more than 20 years of separation, Al-Menem
said, adding that their close ties will benefit the whole region.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Egypt are facing common challenges such as
technological development and globalization, he said, hoping the
countries' scholars can reach better understanding and help improve
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister for Educational and Research
Sadeq Kharrazi said Iran and Egypt have common historical,
religious and cultural bonds and the two should exercise deep
insight toward the future.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Egypt severed diplomatic relations in 1979 after Egypt
gave asylum to Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, the late Iranian shah deposed
in the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Tehran used to slam Cairo for cracking down on Islamic
fundamentalists who tried to overthrow the secular government and
install Islamic rule in Egypt, while Egypt accused Iran of
supporting terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
However, with the foreign policy of detente advocated by Iran's
moderate President Mohammad Khatami since his taking office in
1997, the two countries have markedly improved bilateral relations
and cooperation, especially in the cultural and economic fields.
</P>
<P>
On June 21, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak made a historic
telephone call to President Khatami to congratulate Iran on its new
membership in the Group 15 (G15) developing countries.
</P>
<P>
As it was the first top-contact between the two countries in 21
years of strained relations, many people considered it a prelude to
full resumption of ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
