<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Will Try to Clinch Deal with Arafat: Egyptian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on
Monday expressed readiness and willingness to try to reach a peace
agreement with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat during their
upcoming summit to be hosted by U.S. President Bill Clinton, a
senior Egyptian official said.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Barak
stressed that he will be positive and do his utmost to make the
negotiations successful, Osama al-Baz, political advisor to
Mubarak, said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Barak gave the impression that he is determined to seek a deal
with the Palestinians at the summit in the U.S. Camp David
presidential retreat, al-Baz told reporters in a briefing. The two
leaders did not speak to reporters following the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Barak came to Cairo not to "put a ceiling or mention forbidden
points" in the negotiations with Arafat, but to expound to the
president his view about what he expects to happen at the summit
and what he hopes to achieve, al-Baz said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if Egypt has proposed compromise ideas to Barak, al-
Baz said that Egypt might have some ideas, but it did not submit
any such ideas as formal proposals because it is not a negotiator.
</P>
<P>
It is up to the two negotiating parties to present ideas and
Egypt will try to help without imposing its point of view on any
party, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Barak later headed back to Israel to face a censure motion
against his government in the parliament. Despite the political
turmoil at home, he insisted on flying on to the United States for
Tuesday's summit, which is designed to seek a final peace agreement
between the Palestinians and Israel before a September 13 deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
