<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weizman Supports Barak to Attend Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman on
Monday expressed his support for Prime Minister Ehud Barak to
attend the upcoming three-way summit in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The summit could bring about peace for Israel and Barak must go
and solve the problems with the Palestinians, Weizman told Israel
Radio.
</P>
<P>
Weizman praised Barak for his efforts and courage to reach a
peace agreement with the Palestinians, saying that right now "Barak
is like a field commander commanding charges without help from the
soldiers."
</P>
<P>
Weizman is scheduled to submit his letter of resignation to
Knesset (parliament) Speaker Avraham Burg Monday evening. The
resignation will take effect 48 hours later, ending his seven years
in the post of president.
</P>
<P>
After learning Sunday that the ultra-Orthodox Shas party was to
leave Barak's coalition, Weizman called upon Barak to form "as wide
a government as possible with as few disagreements as possible,"
but stopped short of calling for a national unity government that
will include right-wing opposition Likud party.
</P>
<P>
"It is easy to call for a national unity government. I am always
in favor of a national unity government, but what good would a
national unity government do if there are constant disagreements,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Right-wing and religious parties quit the Barak-led coalition
government one by one, accusing Barak of keeping them in the dark
and being ready to make too many concessions to the Palestinians
without eliciting compromises from the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Natan Sharansky, head of a right-leaning Russian immigrant
party, Yisrael Ba'aliya, resigned on Sunday as interior minister,
becoming the first coalition partner to turn his back on Barak on
the eve of crucial negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Several hours later, Shas party, the second largest partner in
the coalition, also decided to defect and the National Religious
Party, which represent Jewish settlers, followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Barak's coalition now has only 42 seats in the 120-member
Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
The three-way summit will begin at Camp David, a presidential
resort in Maryland, the United States, on Tuesday with the
participation of Barak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S.
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
It is aimed to reach a framework agreement between Israel and
the Palestinians on final-status issues such as the fate of
Jerusalem, borders, refugees, settlement and water ahead of the
September target for final peace deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
