<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Population Increases by 2.6 Million in Two Months: UNFPA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"India crossed the billion mark on May 11 (this year) and the
country will have an estimated population of 1,002,594,606
tomorrow, which is the World Population Day," UNFPA representative
in India Michael Vlassoff told the press here.
</P>
<P>
India's population growth rate for 1995-2000 is 1.64 percent
compared to the world average of 1.33 percent, said Vlassoff.
</P>
<P>
Though some states in the country, like Kerala, Goa, Tamil Nadu
and Andhra Pradesh, have achieved a fairly low fertility rate
among the local women, these achievements have been offset by
higher total fertility rate in other states, he added.
</P>
<P>
Alarmed at the prospects of a population explosion, India
adopted this year a National Population Policy, the first of its
kind in the south Asian country's history, which set a population
control goal of achieving a total fertility rate of 2.1, or only
two children for each couple, by 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
