<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Will Not Lay Down Arms: Nasrallah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Hezbollah Secretary General Hassan
Nasrallah has denied reports that Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami had asked Hezbollah, or Party of God, to end its military
role in Lebanon and become a political party, Oriental radio
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah said his guerrilla group, which spearheaded the
resistance movement against Israeli occupation of south Lebanon,
will continue activities after the Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed its troop pullout on May 24, ending 22 years of
occupation in south Lebanon. But Hezbollah, supported by both Iran
and Syria, will continue struggle because "the files of Palestine
and Jerusalem will then be opened," Nasrallah said.
</P>
<P>
"The resistance should continue and weapons should be kept in
the hands of Hezbollah and other parties, in a broader resistance,
because Israel will continue to pose a threat to Lebanon's security
and stability," Nasrallah was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon still accuses Israel of a number of encroachments of its
territory despite Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"We have been in accord with President Khatami right from the
beginning that Hezbollah has various spheres of activity to perform
in successive stages," Nasrallah said.
</P>
<P>
"Hezbollah is a resistance movement and a political party at the
same time," he added.
</P>
<P>
The London-based Asharq Al Awsat newspaper on Friday said
Khatami had asked Hezbollah to lay down arms now that Israel had
withdrawn from south Lebanon. Nasrallah visited Tehran early this
month for talks with top Iranian leaders.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah also attacked the upcoming Camp David summit between
U.S. President Bill Clinton, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak as "an attempt to abort the
victory of the resistance" in driving the Israeli occupation army
from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"There is also the looming specter of the loss of the
Palestinian cause. Therefore, the resistance will continue and we
shall stay on in our positions even after the current Israeli
encroachments are terminated," Nasrallah was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
