<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Clarifies Report on Labor Deportation From Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government Monday
contradicted Sunday's press report that some 1,400 Bangladeshi
workers would be deported from Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Bangladesh Mission in Kuala Lumpur, Labor and
Employment Ministry in a clarification Monday said 810 Bangladeshi
workers, now detained in Malaysian deportation camps on charges of
unauthorized entry, overstaying or using forged visas, are
awaiting deportation.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers reported Sunday that Malaysia has started to
expel more than 1,400 Bangladeshis detained for offenses such as
illegal entry, overstaying and possession of fake visas, quoting
official Bernama News Agency of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi labor ministry said in its handout that as part of
their regular hunt for unauthorized immigrants, Malaysian
authorities detained those Bangladeshi workers in eight
deportation camps and are making arrangement to deport them.
Malaysian government will bear the deportation expenses.
</P>
<P>
It said the Bangladesh Mission officials in Kuala Lumpur are in
touch with the camps and issuing travel permits to those who do
not have valid passports.
</P>
<P>
They have also requested the Malaysian authorities to send the
detained Bangladeshis back home as early as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
