<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Arrests American Woman in Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Taliban militia
have arrested an American woman working for a Kabul-based NGO,
along with seven Afghan women for violating Taliban rules, Afghan
sources in Islamabad said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mary Macmakin, working in an NGO namely PAARSA, was arrested
last Friday in Kabul after the Taliban on Thursday issued letters
to all Kabul-based international NGOs, asking them not to recruit
Afghan women.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's Department for Promotion of Virtue and Prevention of
Vice apprehended the American national and her Afghan colleagues.
The Taliban authorities have not given any reason for the action.
</P>
<P>
Eight men who were arrested along with Macmakin were freed on
Sunday, however, the American lady and seven Afghan women are
still in custody, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate reaction either from the United Nations
in Islamabad or from the United States. However, a report from
Kabul suggest that Ellien Dethot, U.N. Coordinator in Kabul has
lodged protest with Taliban and demanded immediate release of
Macmakin.
</P>
<P>
The radical Islamic militia of Taliban barred women from
employment after they captured the capital of Kabul in September,
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
