<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Special Envoy Visits Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has sent a special envoy to thank the Czech government
for its support during the island worst military crisis, a
government statement said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Media Minister Mangala Samaraweera met Czech President Vaclar
Havel on Sunday, said the statement, handing a letter of thanks
from Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
"President Havel expressed his appreciation for this kind of
gesture and promised continued support," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Samaraweera will meet Czech officials during the next two days
to discuss matters of mutual interest, especially trade between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In April, Sri Lanka turned to Czech and other six countries for
arms to counter a ferocious offensive launched by Tamil Tiger
rebels who overran several key army camps in an apparent attempt
to retake their former stronghold of the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government troops with reinforcements and newly
purchased arms have stalled the rebel offensive since May and
even started to conduct counteroffensives to regain lost ground.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka last Tuesday sent Cultural Affairs Minister Lakshman
Jayakody as a special envoy to India. Government officials said
that several similar missions will be undertaken shortly. 
</P>
