<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Affects Philippines' Transport System Partly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The alleged nationwide transport
strike in the Philippines failed Monday to paralyze the transport
system in Metro Manila and Central Luzon but seriously affected
some other areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
The strikers were demanding an oil price rollback and non-
implementation of the road users tax and the seat belt law. They
also called for the creation of a special traffic court.
</P>
<P>
The Metro Manila Development Authority said most of the drivers
in the capital did not attend the strike and there were no class
suspension in the city's schools on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Militant strike groups also failed to paralyze the public
transportation in Central Luzon except in Angeles City where
passenger jeepney drivers cooperated on the call for a nationwide
strike.
</P>
<P>
Police said all of the estimated 500 passenger jeepneys
operating in Angeles City kept off the streets on Monday as a sign
of their protest.
</P>
<P>
However, there were no stop of public transportation in the
provinces of Bulacan, Nueva Ecija, Bataan, Tarlac, Zambales.
</P>
<P>
In Cebu City in central Philippines, three major transport
groups which count some 3,500 members attended the strike,
paralyzing the city's traffic and prompting schools in that city
to suspend classes.
</P>
<P>
The government fielded buses and other vehicles in the country'
s major cities to help ferry commuters affected by the strike.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora appealed earlier Monday to
militant groups to consider the consequences of their strike,
saying this would not in any way contribute to economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Zamora noted that the recent oil price hikes were a result of
developments in the global market, of which the government has no
control of.
</P>
<P>
A transport strike, Zamora said, would only add to the people's
woes and defeat government efforts to minimize the effects of oil
prices hikes on the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
