<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French President Calls for World Solidarity to Combat AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques
Chirac Monday urged the international community to create world
solidarity to combat AIDS, which has caused severe economic and
social regression, especially in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Chirac's speech was delivered by the country's Health Minister
Dominique Gillot at the 13th International AIDS Conference which
opened in Durban, South Africa, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The president said, "It would be pointless to talk about ethics,
it would be pointless to talk about universal rights, if we are
not able to create world solidarity against AIDS."
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the fight against the virus had been
fighting on two fronts -- in developing and developed nations.
</P>
<P>
He cited statistics which showed that since 1997 more than 33
million people have been infected by the virus, more than 16
million have died, about 3 million of which were in 1999 alone,
with Africa and Asia being the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
"When 90 percent of people infected with HIV live in the
developing world, it would be entirely unthinkable to accept a two-
speed epidemic," he said, "Since 1997, France has stated that
there cannot be two ways of fighting against AIDS : Northern
treatment and Southern prevention."
</P>
<P>
Chirac stressed that "everything possible" should be done to
ensure that new treatments be made available to those most in need
-- Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
The president implored authorities world-wide to implement an
agreement recently signed by UNAIDS -- an integrated body of
United Nations agencies -- and pharmaceutical companies to
radically reduce the cost of drugs for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
This would constitute "an important step forward", he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
