<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Foreign Ministers Back New Banana Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- European Union foreign ministers
on Monday backed the European Commission's new proposals to break
the banana import deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers' general affairs council expressed
support for the "first come, first served" proposals put forward
by the commission, the executive body of the 15-nation bloc, on
July 5.
</P>
<P>
The council asked the commission to report on the outcome of
the proposed banana import scheme.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been striving to work out new banana import systems
that comply with the rules of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
But months of efforts to settle the trade row over banana
imports have met a deadlock, commission officials admitted.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is under pressure to solve the dispute
because the United States has imposed 191 million U.S. dollars of
sanctions on EU goods in retaliation for its banana quota system.
</P>
<P>
Equator, the world's leading exporter of banana, has been
authorized by the WTO to slap 201 million dollars of sanctions on
EU goods.
</P>
<P>
The WTO sided with Latin American countries and the United
States that argued that the current EU quota rules favored EU
territories and former European colonies in the Caribbean over
Latin American exporters and U.S. marketing companies.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the European Commission proposed that the EU
move to a tariff-only banana import system by January 1, 2006,
after a transitional period involving a complex tariff rate quota
system.
</P>
<P>
Yet intense discussions with the United States and other Latin
American countries failed to enable the EU to come up with a way
to divide the quota that satisfies all parties.
</P>
<P>
Under the new proposals, the European Commission will push for
a transitional system of tariff quotas that would be allotted on a
"first come, first served" basis while the tariff-only system
would take effect in 2006 as previously proposed.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that if no agreement could be reached on
the "first come, first served" basis by mid-October this year, it
planned to start negotiations on a tariff-only system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
