<HEADLINE> Canadian Swimmer Wins Men's 100-metre Freestyle in Vancouver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Canadian swimmer Yannick Lupien
captured the gold medal in the men's 100-metre freestyle at an
international swimming competition staged Sunday in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
At the Mel Zajak Invitational swim meet, Lupien, 20, finished
in 50.74 seconds for the win. His rival compatriot Craig Hutchison
was second in 51.43. Adam Messner of the U.S. took the third place
in 51.66.
</P>
<P>
In other events, Japanese swimmer Takashi Yamamoto won both the
50 and 200 butterfly, while the men's 1,500 freestyle title went
to Canada's Olympian Andrew Hurd.
</P>
<P>
In women's competition, American Olympic champion Jenny
Thompson won both 50 butterfly and 100 freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Kelly Stefanyshyn claimed the 100 backstroke. Another
Canadian woman swimmer Jennifer Button won the 200 butterfly and a
third compatriot Karine Legault took the 800 freestyle.
</P>
<P>
The Vancouver swim meet was a training competition featuring
the 36 Olympic team members, according to Canadian organizers.
</P>
</TEXT>
