<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Over the coming three years, Coca Cola is going to
invest 200 million U.S. dollars in building a marketing base and
updating the equipment of its Bahrain-based regional beverage
plant.
</P>
<P>
This step was related to the transfer of Coco Cola's regional
bureau to Bahrain to supervise the business in 25 regional
countries.
</P>
<P>
MASCAT -- Oman's trade balance registered a surplus of 2.3
billion dollars in 1999 against a deficit of 313 million dollars in
the previous year. This boom was attributed to rising oil prices,
increasing oil exports and dwindling imports.
</P>
<P>
Omani exports in 1999 hit 7.13 billion dollars, a hike of 31
percent from 1998 while imports dropped to 4.74 billion dollars, a
decrease of 17.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Trade relations between Turkey and Lebanon have
expanded rapidly in recent years, Laleli Industrialists' and
Businessmen's Association (LASIAD) Chairman Ayhan Karahan said.
</P>
<P>
"We used to transport goods through the sea, now it is largely
done by air. To travel fast and deliver goods in the shortest
possible time is a very important factor in terms of commerce," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Karahan said Lebanon not only buys goods from Turkey, but also
distributes them to other countries in the region due to its
special location.
</P>
<P>
Now the lebanese airlines, which has resumed flights to Libya,
will serve as a bridge linking Turkish producers with the North
African markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Pak-Arab Refinery Limited (Parco), in which Abu
Dhabi's International Petroleum Investment Company (IPIC) and the
Austrian firm OMV jointly hold a 40-percent stake, will commission
its refinery in Pakistan in September.
</P>
<P>
The processing capacity of the refinery, which is located in
Mahmoud Kot in Pakistan, is 4.5 million tons per year, accounting
for 30-40 percent of the country's refining capacity.
</P>
<P>
Light crude will be imported from Abu Dhabi for the refinery,
but the details of the exact amount of import is yet to be
finalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
