<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Birth Rate Reduces 1994-1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's birth rate has dropped
from 3.01 percent to 1.99 percent in the past 10 years, Vietnam
News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese population was 76.324 million with a growth rate of
1.58 percent, far below the forecast, according to the results of
the country's population census, conducted on April 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The average number of children every family expected to have
decreased from 2.79 in 1994 to 2.3 in 1999, and the rate of
contraceptive users among young couples increased from 65 percent
to 75 percent in the 1994-1999 period.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of communes including mountainous ones have obtained
the target of no third child to any families.
</P>
<P>
With its efforts and achievements in population and family
planning movement, Vietnam's State Committee for Population and
Family Planning has been awarded the Labour Order, first class, by
the State President and the United Nations' Population Award 1999.
</P>
<P>
A congress, which held by Vietnam's State Committee for
Population and Family Planning in Hanoi Monday, affirmed that the
orientation for the emulation movement in the next 10 years is to
firmly maintain the declining birth rate trend, slow down the
average annual population growth rate to 1.3 percent and keep the
population at 88 million in 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
