<HEADLINE> Three French Journalists Feared Abducted by Abu Sayyaf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The extremist Abu Sayyaf group
might have abducted three French journalists on Sunday in the
southern Philippines, bringing the number of their hostages to 37,
according to a police report Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report reaching here from the southern Sulu province said
the three journalists failed to return to the provincial capital
of Jolo as of Monday afternoon after they visited the kidnapper's
jungle lair in Talipao town, some 15 kilometers southeast of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
Police identified the three France TV media men as camera man
Jean-Jacques Le Garec, 40, reporter Maryge Burget, 38, and sound
man Roland Madura, 50.
</P>
<P>
This has prompted the French and German embassies in Manila to
order the immediate pull-out of all journalists from their
respective countries covering the now 78-day old hostage crisis in
Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Their group was the latest batch of foreign journalists who
came to personally visit the hostages held by Abu Sayyaf
kidnappers led by Ghali Andang, alias Commander Robot, and Mujib
Susukan.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the group left for Talipao at about 8:00 Sunday
morning but failed to show up as expected, prompting the police to
surmise that the trio were already held against their will.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Abu Sayyaf abducted German journalist Andreas
Lorenz of Der Spiegel magazine.
</P>
<P>
Aside from Lorenz, the Abu Sayyaf has also detained 13
evangelists from the Jesus Miracle Crusdade led by Wilde Almeda.
</P>
<P>
The Christian group trekked to the Abu Sayyaf camp to pray over
the 20 mostly foreign hostages kidnapped by the Abu Sayyaf from a
resort off the coast of Sabah, Malaysia, in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
