<HEADLINE> Nigeria Pledges to Implement Anti-Corruption Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
has reiterated that the civil government will fully implement the
anti-corruption act and nobody will be spared in the crusade to
abolish graft in the country, the This Day newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Obasanjo as saying over the weekend that he
has been ready to accept public scrutiny or investigation of his
activities while in office.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said he has no objection to remove in certain fields
the constitutional immunity granted him, vice-president, governors
and their deputies .
</P>
<P>
He warned ministers and permanent secretaries to steer clear of
corrupt practices, saying any one caught enriching himself will
face the full wrath of the law.
</P>
<P>
The president also challenged the public servants to show
greater commitment, transparency, mutual respect and understanding
as well as patriotism in the discharge of their duties.
</P>
<P>
The anti-corruption act, formally known as the Corrupt
Practices and Related Offense Act 2000, is the first act proposed
by the Obasanjo administration since its inauguration last May.
</P>
<P>
The passage and enactment of the new law was widely believed to
be a major milestone for the restoration of democratic process in
Nigeria after the long-term military rule.
</P>
<P>
The abolition of corrupt practices has been a cardinal
objective of the present administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
