<HEADLINE> EU Members Demand Extended EU-Balkans Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Three European Union member
states on Monday demanded an extended summit between the 15-nation
bloc and the Balkans to include the latters' immediate neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Austria and the Netherlands asked the French
presidency and other EU member states to consider including
Bulgaria, Hungary, Romania and the Czech Republic into the EU-
Balkans summit.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook told his counterparts from
the other EU nations at their general affairs council that
Bulgaria, Hungary, Romania and the Czech Republic all have
historic and ethnic ties with the Balkan nations.
</P>
<P>
"Bulgaria, Hungary and Romania have a long historic and
geographic relations with Serbia and I understand that Croatia,
the host to the summit, would welcome the participation of these
countries," said Cook.
</P>
<P>
France, which took over from Portugal the rotating EU
presidency on July 1, proposed holding a summit participated in by
the EU, the Balkan countries and countries of Albania, Bosnia-
Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, the Yugoslav republic of
Montenegro and the Yugoslav province of Kosovo as well as the
opposition parties of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The summit was proposed to be held in November at the Croatian
seaside resort of Dubrovnik.
</P>
<P>
Some of the EU foreign ministers proposed on Monday that the
summit be held prior to the parliamentary and general elections of
the Balkan countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Austria, Belgium and Sweden proposed at the foreign ministers
council that the union should re-consider its political and
economic sanctions imposed against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"These sanctions are perhaps counterproductive and we need to
re-consider them," said Belgian State Secretary Pierre Chevalier.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said that the European
Union should watch for the reflection of the sanctions with stress
on the effectiveness of the sanctions and the functions of the
EU's objectives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
