<HEADLINE> Venus and Serena Take Women's Doubles Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Venus and Serena Williams became
the first sisters to win the Wimbledon doubles as they cruised to
the victory in the delayed final against fourth seeds Julie Halard-
Decugis and Ai Sugiyama in staight sets 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The win means that Venus becomes the third consecutive women's
singles champion to win the doubles title as well, following
Lindsay Davenport and Jana Novotna.
</P>
<P>
Despite easing to the title, it did not look like becoming the
return to Center Court that Venus would have liked following her
wonderful singles victory.
</P>
<P>
She dropped her opening two service games of the women's
doubles
final, giving opponents Halard-Decugis and Sugiyama a golden
opportunity to take the first set.
</P>
<P>
However, Halard-Decugis, winner of the Wimbledon warm-up
tournament in Eastbourne, did the same as the servers struggled to
take the advantage.
</P>
<P>
While her serving was not up to scratch, Venus's volleying was
perfect and, with her younger sister, were showing team-work not
seen before in the tournament. They did clash rackets at the net
when at set point, but it simply confused their opponents and they
took the lead.
</P>
<P>
The second set was a far more clear cut affair as the Williams
sisters stormed into a 4-0 lead. Halard-Decugis and Sugiyama
fought back bravely, taking two games, but they could not restrain
the power of their opponents as Serena took the match with an ace.
</P>
</TEXT>
