<HEADLINE> East China's Shandong Reports Robust Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
reported robust economic growth in the first half year, according
to a conference here today on the region's economic status.
</P>
<P>
The province's GDP (gross domestic product) rose by 10.3
percent, 2.2 percentage points higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
The performance of its industrial enterprises was the best in
recent years, with the index of enterprise performance surging by
18 percentage points over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The province's export and import volume rose by 37.6 percent to
hit 11.377 billion U.S. dollars. Its retail sales were 9.8 percent
up and investment in fixed assets up 16.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shandong Governor Li Chunting said the performance of the
regional economy is the best in recent years, an indication that
the economy has entered a new period of fast growth.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the record growth to the government's positive
fiscal and financial policies and recovering domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The governor predicted that with China's expected accession to
the World Trade Organization (WTO), the formation of new economic
growth points and the impact of the West Development Strategy,
Shandong's economy would grow faster in the second half of the
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
