<HEADLINE> Writers Donate to Literary Foundation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Four well-known writers who won
the first Lao She Literary Prize have donated money they earned
from book sales to the Lao She Literary and Art Foundation, the
foundation announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The foundation granted the literary prize for the first time in
June and published a compilation of all the winning short novels,
written by Tie Ning, Liu Heng, Ye Guangqin, Lu Tao and Mu Guozheng.
</P>
<P>
Following the book's release, Tie, Liu, Ye and Lu endowed 12,
000 yuan (1,446 U.S. dollars) worth of remuneration of the first
edition to the foundation.
</P>
<P>
The biennial Lao She Prize in Literature, set up to commemorate
late Chinese literary master Lao She, who was former known as Shu
Qingchun, is presented to eminent literary works which have "in-
depth and meaningful text with a distinct local flavor," according
to the judges' committee.
</P>
<P>
Lao She, a native of Beijing, created a number of masterpieces
including the novel "Rickshaw Boy" and the play "Teahouse."
</P>
