<HEADLINE> Bashar Casts Ballot in Syrian Presidential Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Bashar al-Assad, commander-in-
chief of the Syrian Armed Forces, on Monday cast his ballot in a
nationwide referendum which is set to elect him new president of
the republic after his father Hafez al-Assad died of heart attack
last month.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at a polling station in the Damascus-based al-Basel
Institute, Bashar was greeted by officials and voters who turned
out to vote when polling stations opened at 7 a.m. (0400GMT).
</P>
<P>
After casting his vote, Bashar met with a number of teachers at
the institute, where he had received education, and thanked them
for giving him good education.
</P>
<P>
Over 9 million eligible voters of Syria's total population of 17
million are expected to cast their ballots at 11,185 polling
stations.
</P>
<P>
The voting, which will last for 12 hours, may be extended for
three hours in case of a heavy turnout.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Mohammad Harba is due to announce the
referendum result on Tuesday when the 250-member People's Assembly
(parliament) meets for a special session to approve the outcome of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
Within hours of Hafez al-Assad's demise on June 10, the
parliament amended the constitution to lower the age threshold for
a president from 40 to 34. In the days that followed, Bashar, an
eye doctor, was promoted from colonel to general and declared
commander of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
On June 27, the parliament unanimously approved the ruling Baath
Party's nomination of Bashar, 34, for the presidency and set July
10 as the date for the presidential referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
