<HEADLINE> Barak's Security Advisor Optimizes About Summit Outcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Before departing for the Camp
David summit, Israeli Prime Minster Ehud Barak's security advisor
Danny Yatom said here Monday that the chances are good for Barak to
return with a peace accord acceptable to the majority of the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Yatom also reiterated that Israel will not recognize the right
of the Palestinian refugees to return home. He said Barak has not
changed his "red lines" regarding the return of the refugees,
namely, Israel is neither legally nor morally responsible for the
refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "a very small number" of Palestinians may be
permitted to enter Israel on humanitarian grounds.
</P>
<P>
There are about 3.5 million Palestinian refugees now mainly
living in Syria, Jordan and Lebanon. They were driven away from
home during the 1948 and 1967 Middle East wars.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Center Party leader Amnon Shahak said
Monday morning he believes new elections will be held shortly. He
is due to leave for Camp David near Washington to attend the
summit.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Shahak, also minister of
transport, said he believed that there would have to be elections
since Barak could not continue to rely on a narrow coalition.
</P>
<P>
Following the successive resignations of the four-seat Yisrael
Ba'aliya party led by Interior Minister Natan Sharansky, five-seat
National Religious party and the 17-seat ultra-Orthodox Shas party,
Barak's coalition was reduced to a crippling 42-seat minority in
the 120-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing Meretz party, whose three ministers stepped down
in June over Shas's funding crisis, aired the willingness to return
to the government Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Barak also met with Am Ehad party leader Amir Peretz Sunday
night and asked him to join a narrow coalition. Peretz is expected
to respond to the proposal on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Barak and his negotiation team are heading for the crucial
three-way summit in Camp David later on Monday in a bid to clinch a
framework deal for the settlement of the thorniest issues,
including the status of Jerusalem, the future of Jewish
settlements, borders, water, security and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The defection of the three ruling partners on the eve of the
negotiations has overshadowed the prospects for the summit, which
have already drawn extensive doubts due to the wide gaps between
the Israeli and Palestinian stances on key issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
