<HEADLINE> Iraq Willing to Promote Cooperation With Belgium: Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraq is willing to develop
relations with Belgium and hopes to enhance bilateral cooperation,
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made the remarks while meeting with visiting Belgian
Minister of Agriculture Juzai Habart, who arrived here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is keen to resume cooperation with Belgium "in all fields",
said Aziz, adding that Iraq has no discord with Belgium in
particular, and Europe in general.
</P>
<P>
It is high time for the two countries to restore their normal
relations in the interests of the two countries and peoples, said
Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that many European countries have been calling for
lifting the U.N. embargo imposed on Iraq since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian minister pledged that after his visit, he will make
efforts to help get the embargo lifted.
</P>
<P>
Habart expressed his country's readiness to cooperate with Iraq
in various fields, especially in the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Belgium is one of the European countries vying for a slice of
Iraq's lucrative market.
</P>
<P>
Economic delegations from many European countries, including
France, Italy, Germany, Spain, Austria and Bulgaria, have visited
Iraq this year for closer trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Iraq hopes to enhance trade relations with European, Arab and
other countries as a means to alleviate the crippling impacts of
the stringent U.N. sanctions imposed on the country since its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
