<HEADLINE> Lebanon Tries to Save National Supermarket Bloc From Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Economy Ministry and the
Central Bank are due to hold emergency talks Monday to save the
Cooperative Supermarket Bloc from bankruptcy, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
The looming bankruptcy of the debt-ridden chain of cooperative
supermarkets across Lebanon would turn some 2,000 more Lebanese
workers jobless and ruin some 25,000 shareholders.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Industrial Association Jack Sarraf and the board
chairman of the supermarket bloc Munir Farghal are expected to
attend the meetings, to be co-chaired by Economy Minister Nasser
Saidi and Central Bank Governor Riad Salameh.
</P>
<P>
Farghal held a lengthy meeting with Prime Minister Salim Hoss
Sunday during which he revealed that sales of the supermarket chain
had lately slumped by 3.5 million U.S. dollars a month as a result
of recession, spiraling debts and the cessation of goods supplies
because arrears have not been paid to suppliers.
</P>
<P>
The overall debts of the bloc totaled about 103 million dollars
or more, the Safir newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank is seeking to reschedule the debts while
Economy Minister Saidi will explore the possibility of French
partnerships to shore up the hard-hit sector, Al Mustaqbal
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Safir paper quoted unidentified sources at the supermarket bloc
as saying that an "organized apparatus" is orchestrating the drive
to bankrupt the cooperatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
