<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Manila Landslide Rises to 32 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said the
death toll in a landslide which struck the dumpsite in Payatas,
Quezon City of Metro Manila Monday morning has risen to 32 as of 6:
30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Ismael Mathay, mayor of Quezon City, told reporters Monday
evening that more than 500 families were affected and 100 shanties
were buried in the 9.14-meter landslide in Payatas dumpsite.
</P>
<P>
He added that 38 people were hospitalized and 780 others were
in an evacuation center.
</P>
<P>
Most of the dead were children. Mathay said they were trapped
in their shanties because classes were suspended in Quezon City on
account of the strike.
</P>
<P>
Fears were ripe that the casualty count may still rise, with
the probers still uncertain as to how many, exactly, are still
buried and considered missing in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said teams from various
government offices have joined efforts in trying to retrieve the
dead and possibly rescue some more survivors.
</P>
<P>
Non-government organizations have also sent their own forces
and facilities to help in the rescue mission. The search and
rescue operations will continue during the night.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said President Joseph Estrada had ordered the provision
of everything needed by the victims of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Mathay said the shanties were inhabited by squatters who were
once resettled to other safer places but kept on returning, saying
that the place is their only source of livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Due to a week of continuous monsoon rains, the tons of garbage
must have loosened which resulted to its erosion and eventually
became a "landslide said Mathay.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy was precipitated by a tornado compounded by a fire
caused by faulty electrical wiring which added to the misery of
the victims.
</P>
<P>
There were about 50,000 people residing in Payatas. The open
dumpsite was scheduled to be closed in October 1999, but the
closure was held back for lack of an alternative disposal site for
Quezon City's more than 700 tons of daily garbage.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, at least two children died as a result of a similar
garbage landslide in the Payatas open dumpsite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
