<HEADLINE> EU-Funded Reconstruction Project to Start in Mozambique  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Reconstruction projects for
Mozambique funded by the European Union (EU) will get under way in
August, with an aim to repair the damages caused by the
devastating flooding in the southeast African country, said
reports reaching here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The program outlined by the EU includes the rebuilding of the
urban infrastructures in the Chokwe town and the Xai-xai city,
located in south Mozambique near the Limpopo River, which flooded
in February and March, inundating a large area of fields and
destroying a lot of houses.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation of the flood control projects along the
Limpopo River is also considered as a priority of the EU-funded
program, according to the reports issued by the Portuguese Lusa
Agency.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at the donors conference on Mozambican
reconstruction held in May, the European Union promised a sum of
67 million euros ( about 71.6 million U.S. dollars ).
</P>
<P>
The EU commissioner for development and humanitarian aid, Poul
Nielson, said last weekend in Brussels that  2 million euros (2.1
million dollars) of the amount had been earmarked for immediate
projects, 13.5 million euros (14.2 million dollars) to support the
Mozambican government and 18 million euros (19 million dollars) to
recuperate urban infrastructures and protect the rural population.
</P>
</TEXT>
