<HEADLINE> Uganda Increases Power Export to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has gradually increased its
power export to Kenya from 10 megawatts in June to 70 megawatts in
the near future, Ugandan Energy Minister Syda Bumba told Xinhua
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The increase will not affect Ugandan consumers, because we are
exporting the power during the off-peak period between 11 p.m. and
6 a.m.," she said, adding that "instead of wasting that power, we
decided to export it to Kenya."
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Kenya are negotiating the new tariffs on the export,
which will be finalized after the completion of negotiations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has an installed capacity of 243 megawatts, while total
estimated peak demand on the system is 280 megawatts, leaving a
power deficit of 40 megawatts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
