<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 72nd Session of Council of Ministers Ends in Lome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The 72nd Session of Council of
Ministers in charge of preparing for the 36th annual summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) ended Monday morning, just
several hours ahead of the opening of the summit here with
compromise on the creation of the African Union whose headquarters
will be in Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day session, the foreign ministers discussed a
lot of issues especially the creation of the African Union, an
initiative put forward by Libyan leader Muammar Ghaddafi at the
extraordinary summit of OAU in September 1999 in Syrte, Libya.
</P>
<P>
All member states agreed with the principle of the creation of
the Pan-African organization to replace the OAU, but differences
emerged over the issue during the discussions.
</P>
<P>
Some members like South Africa advocated a progressive
establishment of the African Union, while members like Libya
stressed that the union was an absolute necessity and that it
should be put in place no later than 2001 as stipulated in the
Syrte Declaration. The rest of members ruled out the possibility
of the union as the Charter of the OAU was still effective.
</P>
<P>
The draft treaty on the establishment of the African Union will
be high on the agenda of the summit which opens later Monday
morning to be attended by more than 30 African heads of state and
government.
</P>
<P>
Said Djinnit, assistant secretary general of the OAU for
political affairs, told a news briefing Sunday evening that there
was no hesitation at all within the OAU on the need of
establishing the African Union, and the debate mainly revolved
around the speed, the nature and the form of the proposed union.
</P>
<P>
He said the council of ministers also discussed ways to end
various conflicts on the continent: Angola, Burundi, the
Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Comoros and
Somalia, and called for international assistance to the refugees
and displaced people as a result of war and natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
They also recommended a series of measures to punish those
regimes taking power through coup, such as suspension of
participation of the OAU meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0161 </DOCNO>
