<HEADLINE> Kenya to Improve Health Care for Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
addressing women reproductive health seriously with the recent
adoption of a sessional paper on population and sustainable
development by the Parliament , a Kenyan population officer has
said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya would hold the World Population Day celebration next
week in Kisumu city in southwestern Kenya, with the theme "saving
women's lives through provision of better reproductive health",
Kisaya Kisaka was quoted by the East African Standard newspaper as
saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kisaka said at present 590 mothers in Kenya die out of every
100,000 live births due to maternity related deaths, urging the
government to improve reproductive health to reduce maternal
mortality rate.
</P>
<P>
Improved education for women would also help ensure reduction
of such deaths, he added.
</P>
<P>
The officer noted that a health survey conducted in 1998
indicated a sharp decline in infertility rates in Kenya, noting
that the country's total fertility rate is now 4.7 children per
women down from 5.4 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
This also indicated improved awareness on the use of
contraceptive methods in spacing births, Kisaka said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
