<HEADLINE> Zambian Peacekeepers in Sierra Leone Re-equipped  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Fresh supplies including military
hardware have been sent to Zambian soldiers serving under the
United Nations (U.N.) peace-keeping mission in Sierra Leone, Army
Commander Geojogo Musengule has confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian peacekeeping troops in Sierra Leone had been
captured and stripped by the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) led
by Foday Sanko, with their firearms and military hardware seized,
Times of Zambia Monday quoted the commander as saying.
</P>
<P>
Musengule said on Sunday the equipment has been sent to Sierra
Leone's capital of Freetown, adding that the Zambian government,
in collaboration with the U.N., secured the equipment for the
Zambian peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
He said the Zambian contingent would continue to serve as long
as the mission continued.
</P>
<P>
"The contingent that is in Sierra Leone has a mandate of six
months and should the period elapse before the mission is cut,
another unit from Zambia will go and replace those currently there,
" Musengule said.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation was calm in Sierra Leone and the soldiers
were in full operation.
</P>
<P>
The RUF rebels grabbed weapons, among which were armored cars
and uniforms from about 400 Zambian soldiers after capturing them
in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
