<HEADLINE> Angola, Portugal Sign Cooperation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Angola has signed an indicative
program of cooperation worth 20 million U.S. dollars with Portugal,
a source of the Angolan Foreign Ministry said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The accord, rubricated by the Angolan Foreign Minister Joao
Miranda and his Portuguese counterpart Jaime Gama, will cover
actions of education, public works and energy in Angola, a
Portuguese-speaking southwest African country.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement signed at the weekend in Lisbon,
these actions of cooperation for the period 2000-2003 will also
fund the fight against poverty, entrepreneurial support, social
communication, construction and the creation of infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
During the signing ceremony, Joao Miranda announced that Angola
has disbursed 30 million U.S. dollars for an emergency program,
which allowed a slow solution to the most serious problems with
the populations. He added that the humanitarian situation in
Angola is improving substantially as result of the reduction of
the number of war displaced persons and the needy children.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan minister paid a two-day official visit to Portugal
at the invitation of the Portuguese government, with the aim to
discuss issues on the strengthening of bilateral relations. During
his first official visit to Portugal since he took office in
January 1999, Joao Miranda was audienced by the Portuguese
President Jorge Sampaio, to whom he delivered a message from the
Angolan head of state Jose Eduardo dos Santos. 
</P>
