<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Only four Chinese cities --
Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan, Changsha and Lanzhou -- reported slight air
pollution today, with the highest reading at 134.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center today, level-two, or fairly good
air quality, was found in 26 cities: Beijing, Tianjin, Hohhot,
Shenyang, Dalian, Changchun, Harbin, Nanjing, Hefei, Fuzhou,
Nanchang, Jinan, Yantai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Guangzhou, Shenzhen,
Zhuhai, Shantou, Zhenjiang, Nanning, Chongqing, Chengdu, Xi'an,
Xining and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulate matter less than 10 microns in size was the major
pollutant in most of these cities, except Nanning and Chongqing,
where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Xiamen, Qingdao,
Haikou, Guiyang, Kunming, Lhasa and Yinchuan reported excellent
air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution indexes below 50),
level-two or fairly good (pollution indexes ranging from 50 to 100)
, level-three or slightly polluted (pollution indexes ranging from
101-200), level-four or poor (pollution indexes ranging from 201
to 300) and level-five or hazardous (pollution indexes over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in economically developed coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
