<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Amend Traffic Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish parliamentary commission
has decided to work through the three-month summer recess to
prepare for reforming the traffic laws to curb the sharp rise of
the number of accidents which claimed 60,000 lives in the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
The traffic investigative commission, established one day before
the parliament closure for the recess at the beginning of July,
will submit a reform bill in October for debate, local media
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decision to form such a commission was prompted by a
mourning father who walked from Istanbul to Ankara in an effort to
raise public awareness of Turkey's grave traffic problem which
seriously injured or disabled one million people in the past 10
years.
</P>
<P>
Boray Uras, who lost his beloved daughter Selin and Selin's
fiance
in Istanbul last April, covered the 450-kilometer-long journey for
more than 20 days, an action that shocked Ankara. Dozens of
deputies signed a letter urging the parliament to amend traffic
laws.
</P>
<P>
The commission chairman, Ahmet Tan, said that it would identify
shortcomings in Turkey's driver education, infrastructure and
regulations, and collect opinions from universities and
institutions.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Turkey had lost more people to traffic
accidents than to wars and devastating earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
The great number of accidents was attributed to overspeed,
carelessness and insufficient training for drivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
