<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli NRP Ministers Submit Letters of Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Minister of Construction
and Housing Yitzhak Levy, also leader of the National Religious
Party (NRP), Monday submitted his letter of resignation to Prime
Minister Ehud Barak before Barak left for Egypt.
</P>
<P>
NRP's two deputy ministers, Deputy Education Minister Shaul
Yahalom and Deputy Minister of Religious Affairs Yigal Bibi, also
resigned automatically.
</P>
<P>
Barak said as he accepted the letters that his heart was torn
apart over the future of Judea and Samaria (the ancient Jewish view
of the West Bank).
</P>
<P>
The NRP Central Committee held a meeting in Tel Aviv Sunday
evening and authorized its ministers to resign from Barak's
coalition. NRP opposes to Barak's attendance at a three-way summit
slated for Tuesday at Camp David near Washington, which will also
be attended by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S. President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The summit is aimed at solving the differences between Israel
and the Palestinians on key issues such as the status of Jerusalem,
borders, refugees and settlements and trying to reach a framework
agreement for their settlement.
</P>
<P>
Barak's two other coalition partners, the ultra-Orthodox
religious Shas party and Yisrael Ba'aliya of Russian immigrants,
left Barak's coalition on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of the three parties took Barak's government down
to 13 cabinet ministers from 22 and reduced his coalition from 68
seats in the 120-member Knesset (parliament) to 42.
</P>
<P>
Barak will return to Israel later Monday from Egypt after
holding talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak ahead of
Tuesday's summit.
</P>
<P>
He will leave for Washington in the evening after Knesset's
voting on the motions of no-confidence against him submitted by the
opposition Likud party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
