<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade with South Countries Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's trade with South
countries increased by 7.6 percent in 1999 over that in 1998,
according to International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah
Aziz Monday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's trade with these countries amounted to 97.2 billion
ringgit (25.57 billion U.S. dollars) in 1999 against 90.3 billion
ringgit (23.76 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998, she said when
opening the 14-day familiarization program for officials of
Investment Promotion Agencies of developing countries here
organized by the Malaysian Industrial Development Authority and
the Malaysian Technical Cooperation Program.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, exports to these countries last year
amounted to 56.8 billion ringgit (14.94 billion U.S. dollars), up
4.1 percent, while imports stood at 40.4 billion ringgit (10.63
billion U.S. dollars), up 12.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, China, India, the Philippines and Indonesia were the
five major South nations for the country's exports last year.
</P>
<P>
She said that major exports to South countries in 1999 were
electrical and electronic products, palm oil, crude petroleum and
chemical and chemical products.
</P>
<P>
She said that to facilitate trade and investments with South
countries, Malaysia has so far signed 54 trade agreements, 52
investment guarantee agreements and 26 bilateral payment
agreements.
</P>
<P>
She said the Malaysian South-South Association and its
investment arm -- Malaysia South-South Corporation, are constantly
making efforts to promote bilateral trade and investments with
South countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
