<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Killed in Manila Dumpsite Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- At least six children have been
confirmed dead and many others hurt after incessant rains caused a
landslide Monday morning in a mountain-high garbage dump site in
Metro Manila, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
Ismael Mathay, mayor of Quezon City where the dumpsite was
located, said some 70 shanties in Barangay (village) Payatas
inhabited by squatters who are earning a living by scavenging in
the dumpsite were buried under tons of domestic waste and garbage.
</P>
<P>
Mathay said the shanties were inhabited by squatters who were
once resettled to other safer places but kept on returning, saying
that the place is their only source of livelihood.
</P>
<P>
He added that search and rescue operation is now the order of
the day and the city government is exerting all efforts and
mobilizing all available resources to help the squatter-victims
and their families.
</P>
<P>
Due to a week of continuous monsoon rains, the tons of garbage
must have loosened which resulted to its erosion and eventually
became a "landslide", said Mathay.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy was precipitated by a tornado compounded by a fire
caused by faulty electrical wiring which added to the misery of
the victims.
</P>
<P>
There were about 50,000 people residing in Payatas. The open
dumpsite was scheduled to be closed in October 1999, but the
closure was held back for lack of an alternative disposal site for
Quezon City's more than 700 tons of daily garbage.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, at least two children died as a result of a similar
garbage landslide in the Payaas open dumpsite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
