<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Tanzania's Land Threatened With Desertification  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Almost half of Tanzania's
land is now under the threat of desertification due to increased
human activities, the independent Guardian newspaper reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The problem which in recent years was only confined to some
parts of central Tanzania has now spread to areas which are
hitherto not thought to be in danger of desertification.
</P>
<P>
The rate of desertification in Tanzania has surpassed efforts
to combat it, Richard Muyungi, assistant director of Environment
in the Vice-President's Office, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
This is mainly due to adverse weather changes and increased
human activity, explained Muyungi, adding that in some parts it
was caused by overstocking.
</P>
<P>
This is particularly the case in central Tanzania where there
are pastoralists with large herds of livestock, which exceed the
carrying capacity of the land and lead to overgrazing, said
Muyungi.
</P>
<P>
Other causes include deforestation, over-cultivation, excessive
mismanaged irrigation and over-population, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said refugees fled into the country are also causing
desertification, because when they settle in an area in large
numbers, they cut down all the trees and destroy vegetation.
</P>
<P>
However, Muyungi said efforts are being made by various
organizations and institutions to combat this problem and they
have managed to raise people's awareness on desertification.
</P>
<P>
While some NGOs are engaged in land management programs in
areas threatened with desertification, the Vice-President's Office
has been offering support to various district councils to that
effect in terms of expert advice as well as material support, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Most bare lands in Tanzania today were covered with thick
evergreen forests between 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Increasing populations pressure, cutting of wood for charcoal,
bush fires, and development of industries have made the country
lose 300,000 to 400,000 hectares of forests a year, while less
than 200,000 hectares of forests are planted annually,
environmentalists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
