<HEADLINE> Blast Kills Six in Russia's North Ossetia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Six people were killed and 15
others wounded in a bomb explosion in Russia's southern city of
Vladikavkaz, capital of the North Ossetia Republic, on Sunday,
reported the Interfax news agency Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest reports, two people were killed on the
spot and four others, one of them a police officer, died in
hospital, Interfax cited an official in the North Ossetian
Interior Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The investigators are not sure yet whether the bombing was the
work of Chechen rebels, he said.
</P>
<P>
The blast was caused by an explosive device, packed in a small
handbag and planted under a car parked in a square near the market,
at 11:15 a.m. Moscow time (0815 GMT), the Itar-Tass cited the
North Ossetian Interior Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The blast was about 50 meters from the site of the explosion in
the same market on March 19, 1999, which killed 52 people and
wounded some 200, said the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
