<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Apologizes to All Soccer-playing Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Soccer chief
executive said in Auckland Monday that New Zealand Soccer will
apologize to every soccer-playing nation for Friday's action of
Charlie Dempsey, president of Oceania Football Confederation (OFC).
</P>
<P>
South Africa will receive a "special" letter of apology after
the New Zealander on Friday ignored OFC instructions and failed to
support South Africa's bid to host the 2006 World Cup, the
Television NZ quoted Bill MacGowan as saying Monday in the biggest
city of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Dempsey abstained from the vote in Zurich, effectively giving
the event to Germany.
</P>
<P>
"We will be apologizing. We certainly will be," Chief Executive
MacGowan of New Zealand Soccer said.
</P>
<P>
"We will write, today, to all countries associated with FIFA,
explaining New Zealand Soccer's position because I think New
Zealand Soccer's taken too much of the brunt of this decision,
only because Charlie resides here, and stuff coming off the news
wires all over the world, it was a New Zealand Soccer decision,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
MacGowan noted Dempsey's abstention from voting "is clearly not
a New Zealand Soccer decision."
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, 79-years-old Dempsey, after
meeting OFC delegates in Auckland on Sunday, announced he would
retire at the end of September, two years earlier than planned.
</P>
<P>
He said he decided not to vote because he had been put under "
intolerable pressure" by supporters of the competing bids,
including attempts to bribe him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
