<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- On the eve of his departure for Camp David, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak Sunday brushed off his coalition crisis and
turned to the public with a plea to support him in his endeavors.
</P>
<P>
"I need to stand above all these political differences and all
these party considerations and to make every possible effort in the
search for a peace agreement which will end the bloodshed between
us and our neighbors," Barak said in a televised press conference.
</P>
<P>
Barak promised that, if a peace agreement is reached, he will
bring it before the people in a referendum, and further pledged to
abide by the "red lines" he set out for himself.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- With his coalition slashed in one day from 68 to 42 Knesset
(Parliament) members following the resignation of three parties,
Barak Monday departs as the head of the Israeli delegation to the
Camp David summit meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
U.S. President Bill Clinton for reaching an Israeli-Palestinian
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
For the third time since the inception of the government a year
ago, the religious Shas party Sunday announced its resignation from
the coalition, this time citing Barak's refusal to spell out his "
red lines" in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Natan Sharansky's Yisrael Ba'aliya party also
resigned Sunday, Construction and Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy's
National Religious Party will follow suit Monday, after getting the
go-ahead from his party's Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Minister David Levy announced that he would
not join Barak at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The disintegration of Barak's government is causing serious
concerns in the United States. The Americans are worried that Barak
will arrive at the crucial Camp David summit without a majority in
the Knesset (Parliament) and effectively without a government.
</P>
<P>
The slashing statements made recently by Foreign Minister David
Levy and his decision not to attend the summit meeting heightened
the administration's fears that Barak may not be in a position to
make the historic decisions the Camp David meeting will require.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians' announcement that they, like Israel, will hold
a referendum on any agreement, with the voters to include the
Palestinian refugees, only reinforced the Americans' evaluation
that the prospects for the summit's success are not good.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli President Ezer Weizman will submit his letter of
resignation to Knesset Speaker Avraham Burg Monday. It will take
effect 48 hours later, ending his seven years in office and a long
career of service.
</P>
<P>
Speaking shortly after Shas leader Eli Yishai announced his
party's intention to leave the coalition, Weizman called upon Prime
Minister Ehud Barak to form "as wide a government as possible with
as few disagreements as possible," but stopped short of calling for
a national unity government.
</P>
<P>
Arye Shumer, director general of Weizman's Office, will submit
the resignation letter on Weizman's behalf to Burg, who will serve
as interim president until a new president is elected July 31 and
sworn in on August 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
