<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji's Coup Leader Excludes Indians from New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's coup leader George Speight
excluded Monday the ethnic Indians and other nationalities from a
new government.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Associated Press AAP, Speight said
the new government would be open to indigenous Fijians only for at
least the next two years, excluding ethnic Indians and other
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
He signed an agreement Sunday night with the military
authorities letting the Great Council of Chiefs to select a
president and a voice president latter this week and he will
release on Thursday all 27 hostages held in the parliament complex
since May 19.
</P>
<P>
Speight laid the blame on the military for the protracted
negotiations over a solution to the Pacific island's crisis. He
accused the military of colluding with former president Ratu
Kamisese Mara and the 1987 year coup leader Sitiveni Rabuka.
</P>
<P>
"They have tried all they can to manipulate the army in order
to serve their own means to get rid of us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speight said the political ambitions of Rabuka were finished,
while his own future was up to the Council of Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
Speight reiterated he did not plan to be part of the new
government, although he would consider it if specifically invited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
