<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loan to Ease Kenya's Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will cut its power rationing
by half, from 12 hours to six hours a day, following the World
Bank's approval of a 75-million-U.S. dollar loan, leading Kenyan
newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The loan will help Kenya install two mobile generators with a
capacity of 75 megawatts and 30 megawatts respectively on the
outskirts of Nairobi, the newspapers quoted Energy Minister
Francis Masakhalia as saying.
</P>
<P>
Masakhalia said his government was in the process of
rehabilitating steam turbines at Kiperu in Mombassa in
southeastern Kenya, which will add another 30 megawatts to the
national grid.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Uganda would soon increase power exports to Kenya
from 50 to 60 megawatts to be used during the night, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
These are part of the measures the Kenyan government has taken
to ease power rationing by October, Masakhalia added.
</P>
<P>
Due to the prolonged drought, power generation has greatly
affected by the low levels of the reservoirs, and Kenya has
introduced an intensifying power rationing nationwide since late
May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
