<HEADLINE> Famine Threatens 50,000 Ugandans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- At least 50,000 people in western
Uganda are facing food shortage after hailstones destroyed the
crops there, the New Vision daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some sub-counties in the Masindi District were greatly affected
by hailstones which destroyed finger millet, cassava, maize and
beans, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Many people had not harvested the crops, and there is now a
threat of famine," Blasto Byabakama, district extension co-
ordinator, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Houses built of mud and wattle there were also destroyed, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
The residents have appealed to the local government in the
district for a tax waiver this financial year, saying that they
could not afford paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
However, District Council Chairman John Majara said that
although the incident was regrettable, there could not be an
automatic tax waiver for the residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
