<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloned Cow Gives Birth to Calf in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A cloned cow gave birth to a female
calf Monday at the Ishikawa Prefectural Livestock Research Center
in Ishikawa Prefecture on the Sea of Japan coast, the center
announced.
</P>
<P>
The cow and calf, born through natural delivery, are both
healthy, the center said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Ministry said it is
the first time that a cow cloned from somatic cells gives birth in
Japan, adding that it is likely also the first such birth in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The cow, Kaga No. 2, was born in August 1998 and became
pregnant through artificial insemination last fall.
</P>
<P>
The birth proved that cows cloned from somatic cells can bear
young as ordinary cows, and the birth has brought scientists
closer to realizing practical uses for cloning, such as improving
the quality and mass production of beef, officials at the center
were quoted as saying by the Kyodo News Service.
</P>
<P>
Kaga No. 2 and its twin Noto No. 2 were the world's first cows
cloned from somatic cells. The center expects Noto No. 2 to give
birth in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
