<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise in Tokyo on Wall Street Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose in Tokyo Monday,
led by information technology (IT) issues which were boosted by
last Friday's surge in New York's Nasdaq composite index, with the
benchmark Nikkei index closing above 17,500 for the first time in
five trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 174.44 points, or 1.00
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 17,572.68.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 16.53 points, or 1.03 percent, to 1,
613.89.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 651.53 million
shares from last Friday's 735.03 million shares, with investors
staying on the sidelines ahead of the Bank of Japan's (BOJ) Policy
Board meeting on July 17, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq's recovery to the 4,000 level last Friday boosted IT-
related issues in Tokyo, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The paper, nonferrous metal and real estate sectors also marked
large gains.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, uncertainty over the bailout plan for financially
troubled department store operator Sogo Co. made investors
hesitant to buy stocks further, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outpaced
losers 825 to 424, with 148 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
