<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Future of NZ's Diplomatic Ties With Fiji On Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Radio NZ Monday quoted Goff as saying that the decision on
whether New Zealand maintains a diplomatic presence would be
affected by any involvement of the coup elements in the new
government.
</P>
<P>
The Fijian military and coup leader George Speight signed an
accord Sunday night that will result in the release of the
remaining 27 hostages this Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The hostages, including former Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry,
have now been held in the parliamentary compound in Suva for over
50 days.
</P>
<P>
The Great Council of Chiefs of Fiji are scheduled to hold a
meeting following the release of the hostages when they will name
a new president, vice president and civilian government to replace
the interim government named by the military last week.
</P>
<P>
After the signing of the accord, Speight spokesman Joe Nata
said he expects that the Council will consult with their group and
that coup supporters would become part of the new administration.
</P>
<P>
Speight himself said he is ecstatic at the signing of the
accord with the military, which he called a great day for Fiji.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand foreign minister said it is good news if the
hostages are released, but bad news that Speight and the people
behind him have achieved their objective.
</P>
<P>
He said he has no hope that the Great Council of Chiefs would
stand up to Speight when it meets on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Goff said if Speight and his people are pulling the strings in
the new Fijian government, the New Zealand government will toughen
its approach, including cutting back on aid, military assistance
and its diplomatic representation in Suva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
