<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Builds Railway Leading to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The construction of the railway
connecting Nepal with India began Sunday in Nepal's border city of
Birgunj, about 600 km southwest of Kathmandu, the Radio Nepal said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 5.4km-long broad-gauge railway will connect Birgunj Inland
Container Depot to India's railway track in Raxaul of Bihar state
and is expected to be completed by November, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Minister for Industry, Commerce and Supplies Ram Krishna
Tamrakar and Indian State Minister for Railways Digvijaya Singh
laid the foundation stone for the railway, it said.
</P>
<P>
The railway, being constructed under India grant assistance,
will provide the landlocked Nepal a direct railway access to the
seaport in India's Calcutta and is expected to reduce the trade
and transit cost by about 30 percent, besides reducing the
administrative hassles in the smooth transportation of goods to
and from India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
