<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Graft Takes 1 Bln Baht From Thai Budget Yearly: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- About 1 billion baht (25.6 million
US dollars) of Thailand's budget is lost to corruption each year,
the National Counter Corruption Commission (NCCC) was quoted by
Monday's The Nation as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The figure is a rough estimate, " NCCC Commissioner Kirkkiat
Pipatseritham stated, adding that some academics predicted the
figure is even greater.
</P>
<P>
The current fiscal year budget is about 800 billion baht (20.5
billion dollars), and the government is now preparing a 900
billion baht (23 billion dollars) for the next fiscal year, which
starts in October.
</P>
<P>
To enhance anti-graft efforts, The NCCC will propose sending
representatives to observe the bidding for any big public project
with a value greater than 500 million baht (12.8 million dollars),
he remarked.
</P>
<P>
The commission is also cooperating with the Non-formal
Education Department to launch campaigns to foster an anti-
corruption sentiment among students, members of the public
services and politicians,according to him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
