<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Offers Aid to Fight Disease along Thai-Myanmar Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization said
it would invest 40 million baht (1.02 million U.S. dollars) to
tackle HIV/Aids, malaria and tuberculosis along the Thai Border
with Myanmar, the Bangkok Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The WHO financial aid would help reduce malaria cases, increase
condom use and cure tuberculosis, Korn Dabbaransi, Thai deputy
prime minister and public health minister, said Sunday at the end
of first meeting of health administrators on bilateral cooperation
in disease control between Thailand and Myanmar in Thai northern
resort city of Chiang Mai.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand has been bearing a cost of over 200 million baht (5.
12 million dollars) every year in taking care of the health of
immigrants from neighboring countries," Korn said, adding that
Thailand is at the stage which it can no longer bear the cost
alone.
</P>
<P>
The health ministries of the two nations hope to reduce malaria
by five percent a year, achieve 100 percent increase in condom use
and enforce "directly observed treatment" by 85 percent in all
districts and towns along the Myanmar border.
</P>
<P>
Due to the incomplete intake of medicines among patients,
malaria and tuberculosis cases were on the increase in Chiang Rai,
Tak, Ranong and Kanchanaburi provinces, all of which bordering
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Malaria cases rose from 100,000 to 120,000 between 1996 to 1998,
the public health ministry said, mostly among foreign migrants
seeking treatment along the border.
</P>
<P>
The ministry was also concerned about the increase of HIV/Aids
cases and reports that 80 percent of female sex workers in the
border towns of Tak, Chiang Rai and Ranong were Myanmar, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Health centers will be set up in border towns in Chiang Rai,
Tak and Ranong to tackle the three major diseases, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
Korn was quoted as saying that the problem would never be
solved without the cooperation of neighboring countries and
international bodies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
