<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Lanka to Consult Tamil Parties on Constitutional Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government of ruling People's Alliance (PA) has planned to
reach consensus with Tamil parties in two weeks and present
constitutional reforms to Parliament for approval before it is
dissolved on August 24.
</P>
<P>
The PA government and the main opposition United National Party
(UNP) reached a landmark consensus last Friday on the
constitutional reforms aimed at ending the long-running ethnic
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The proposed reforms aim to devolve more powers to regions
including one administered by Tamils, in an effort to wean the
minority away from Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels
who have been fighting for a separate homeland called Eelam in Sri
Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
However, the Tamil United Liberation Front (TULF), a mainstream
Tamil political party, has rejected the reforms for the devolution
of power reached by consensus between the PA and the UNP, the
local Island newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted TULF Vice President V. Anandasangaree as
saying that the reforms are no substitute for the federal
structure it had proposed.
</P>
<P>
He said his party will decide whether to accept President
Kumaratunga's invitation for talks Monday after their General
Secretary Sambandan returns from the United Kingdom Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Anandasangaree accused the government of wasting time by
talking to the UNP without going directly to the LTTE.
</P>
<P>
However, the LTTE have rejected the constitutional proposals,
saying the separatist war will continue as the reforms fail to
address the issue of Tamil self-determination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
