<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Trade-related News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major trade-related news released by Xinhua during the past week (
July 3-9)
</P>
<P>
Foreign Trade
</P>
<P>
-- Sinopec International turned out to be China's largest
foreign trade company among the country's top 500, and the
Shanghai-based Orient International (Holdings) Co. Ltd., the
largest exporter among the country's top 200, according to an
official chart.
</P>
<P>
-- China's law-makers are busy reviewing the country's foreign
trade laws and regulations to see if they conform to the World
Trade Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
-- More goods have flowed through the Suifenhe Customs in
northeastern province of Heilongjiang, one of the most important
land ports linking China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
In January-May, the volume of imports and exports reached 1.15
million tons, up 44.2 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
-- China exported 1.88 billion US dollars-worth of toys in the
first five months of this year, up 16.4 percent on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
-- China exported 20.93 million tons of coal in the first five
months this year, up 45.6 percent over the same period of last
year, according to the State Administration of Coal Industry.
</P>
<P>
-- China plans to increase coal exports to about 50 million
tons this year from 39 million tons in 1999 to help relax uphill
oversupply in the domestic market and rescue debt-ridden coal
mines.
</P>
</TEXT>
