<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, July 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
Sunday said that talks at the upcoming David Camp summit will be "
very, very hard" but are crucial to avoid an eruption of violence
in the Middle East region. (Albright-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's left-wing Meretz party, upon learning of
the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party's resignation from the government,
announced on Sunday it is willing to return to the coalition
immediately. (Israel-Meretz-Return)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Sunday that despite the failure of the third test of the proposed
National Missile Defense (NMD) system, President Bill Clinton will
still make his decision on whether to begin building the system.
It would be "irresponsible" for the administration to put off the
decision, Albright said on the ABC program "This Week." (Albright-
Clinton-NMD)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Orange Order's Drumcree parade passed off in
Northern Ireland on Sunday, but hundreds of protesters remained
close to the massive barricade erected by the security forces to
stop the march.
</P>
<P>
Backed by thousands of supporters, the Portadown district lodge
said that it would not be going home after failing to hand in a
letter of protest to security forces preventing them from entering
the nationalist Garvaghy Road area of the town, the BBC reported.
(N.Ireland-Parade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on Sunday
hinted that Tehran is expecting a signal of friendship from the
United States so that the 20 years of hostility between the two
countries can be brought to an end. He indicated that Iran will no
longer consider the U.S. as "a great Satan" if it takes sincere
steps toward mending relations with the Islamic republic. (Iran-
US-Relations) 
</P>
</TEXT>
