<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, South Africa World Cup Qualifier End in Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The 2004 World Cup soccer qualifier
between Zimbabwe and South Africa was abandoned with South Africa
leading 2-0 when Zimbabwean fans went on the rampage, throwing
bottles and stones onto the field with eight minutes left on
normal time in the National Sports Stadium here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Violent fans began throwing bottles onto to the pitch when
Delron Buckley scored his second goal for South Africa and the
police reacted by throwing teargas in all directions to chase the
fans from the stadium.
</P>
<P>
Players were left huddled at the center circle of the pitch, but
were later evacuated by armed police into their changing rooms.
</P>
<P>
Match Commissioner Hisham Azmy told reporters that the results
of the match would stand until they send their report to the
world football governing boy FIFA for recommendations.
</P>
<P>
"The match is officially over," said Azmy,
</P>
<P>
"We have already informed FIFA over the phone. We cannot
continue play under these conditions." he added
</P>
<P>
Though Azmy could not disclose the likely punishment for
Zimbabwe, it is believed that the country might be booted out of
the qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
The match started on a balanced note with both teams showing
determination to attack with Buckley opening the score sheet for
South Africa in the sixth minute.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe struggled towards the end of the first half, but
virtually collapsed in the second half with South Africa pinning
them in their area for most of the half.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe coach Misheck Marimo, who replaced Dutch coach Clemens
Westerhof who was sacked last week for poor results, made three
substitutions in the second half, but it appeared the substitutes
actually worsened play.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup group qualifier is composed of Zimbabwe, South
Africa, Burkina Faso, Guinea and Malawi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
