<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voting to Elect Bashar al-Assad as Syrian President Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The day-long Voting on Monday in a
nationwide referendum to elect Bashar al-Assad president of Syria
ended at 10:00 p.m. (1900 GMT) with a massive turnout.
</P>
<P>
Vote counting started immediately after the closing of the total
11,185 polling stations which opened at 7 a.m. (0400 GMT) across
the country.
</P>
<P>
The referendum was to endorse Bashar, 34, to succeed his late
father, Hafez al-Assad, as the country's new president.
</P>
<P>
So far, there were no official figures for the turnout, but
observers and officials said the participation by Syria's 9.4
million registered voters was massive.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Mohammad Harba is due to announce the
referendum result on Tuesday when the 250-member People's Assembly
(parliament) meets for a special session to approve the outcome of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
Harbah had decided to prolong the referendum for three hours
"because of the massive turnout".
</P>
<P>
The referendum is the last step in formalizing Bashar's swift
rise to power, a month after the death of his father who ruled the
country for almost 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
