<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Leaders Explore Ways to Revitalize Least Developed Continent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 10 (Xinhua) -- More than thirty African heads of
state and government attended the opening session of the 36th
summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) here on Monday,
discussing ways to revitalize the least developed continent in the
world.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim
said the integration and unity of the African states is the only
way for the continent to make great progress in the new century.
</P>
<P>
He told participants in the Togolese Palace of Parliament that
as the forerunners of Africa founded the OAU more than thirty
years ago to get the continent liberated from colonial rule, the
present leaders should explore ways to make it prosperous.
</P>
<P>
"There must be new politics and unconstitutionally changed
governments are no longer accepted," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the function, Malawi President Bakili Muluzi said the time
has come for Africa to meet the challenges on the basis of the
progress it has made over the past years.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the general elections recently held in Zimbabwe as
democratic and successful, setting an example for other countries
in the continent to follow.
</P>
<P>
Algerian President and 35th OAU chairman Abdelaziz Bouteflika
said that while African states are cooperating in cooling old
hotspots, new conflicts are still coming into being.
</P>
<P>
"The conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea shows a harsh
reality in Africa, not to say those in Angola, Somalia, Sierra
Leone and others," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the OAU Declaration in Sirte, Libya last
year gave new momentum to African integration which has been
stepped up since the Abuja Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika called on the developed world, especially the
European countries, to write off the heavy debt burden on African
states in a cooperative way.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Anna appealed the rest
of the world to help Africa revitalize its least developed economy.
</P>
<P>
Africa, hit heavily by conflicts and diseases especially HIV/
AIDS, should take measures to develop its economy by investing in
transport, communication and information technology to meet the
challenges put forward by globalization, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As the wind of changes were blowing in Africa in the 1980s,
the wind of democracy and rule by law is blowing in Africa now,"
Anna said, commending highly the elections held in several African
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the efforts by African states to establish a union is
positive, hoping it will play an important role in cooperation in
economic and peacekeeping sectors.
</P>
<P>
As a long-term observer of OAU summit, Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat also made a speech at the session, expressing
appreciation for the contribution made by African states in
Palestine's justified struggle for an independent state over the
past years.
</P>
<P>
Arafat reconfirmed that a Palestinian state will be established
on September 13 this year.
</P>
<P>
Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema, who was elected new
chairman of OAU, stressed that there should be a new change for
African development in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The time has come for Africa to set up an African Union similar
to the European Union which will speed up the integration of
economies in the continent, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Following America and Europe but before Asia, Africa will have
its union to boost the establishment of an economic community and
a common market," he said. "A new united and prosperous Africa
will also strengthen the establishment of democracy and human
rights."
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit meeting will mainly focus on three themes:
regional cooperation and integration, security and stability, and
the challenges of widespread AIDS and poverty in Africa.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss the draft treaty on the establishment of
the African Union initiated during an extraordinary summit on
September 9, 1999 in Sirte, Libya as well as the treaty on the
African Economic Community.
</P>
<P>
Ways to end various conflicts on the continent, particularly in
Angola, Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Sierra
Leone, and the related situation of refugees will also be on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Founded on May 25, 1963, OAU is designated to promote the unity
and solidarity of the African states, defend the sovereignty,
territorial integrity and independence of members, coordinate and
intensify the cooperation and efforts to achieve a better life for
the people of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Following eradicating all forms of colonialism, the
organization has been focused on peace and development of the
African continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
