<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Plaintiffs Request $196 Billion From Tobacco Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Plaintiffs Monday
requested 196 billion dollars in punitive damages from the tobacco
industry for smoking-related illness and death.
</P>
<P>
"This industry has left a half-century trail of deceit which
has decimated millions of Americans," said Stanley Rosenblatt, a
lawyer for the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
"Never have so few caused so much harm to so many for so long,
and the day of reckoning has arrived," he told the jury as closing
arguments for the two-year trial began in Miami, Florida.
</P>
<P>
A verdict is expected in the penalty phase of the case by the
end of the month. Circuit Judge Robert Kaye last week rejected a
request from the tobacco firms to limit penalties to 15 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Each side has two days to summarize the class-action case on
behalf of 300,000 to 700,000 sick Florida smokers against the
nation's five biggest cigarette makers,including Philip Morris Inc.
and R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.
</P>
<P>
Any decision will be appealed and the case is expected to take
at least two years to move through Florida appeal courts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish President Visits Russia to Improve Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Alexander
Kwasniewski paid a one-day working visit to Russia Monday for
improving bilateral relations, which have worsened to an ice point
since the two countries' exchange of expulsions of diplomats and a
hooligan attack against the Russian diplomatic building in Warsaw
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski's visit to Russia is "more than timely," Russian
President Vladimir Putin told the press after his meeting with
Kwasniewski in the Kremlin, highly appraising the Polish president
's trip to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The two sides mainly discussed the aspects of Russian-Polish
relations, bilateral economic issues, ways of coordinating their
actions in the international arena and broadening cultural and
humanitarian contacts, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Thanking Kwasniewski "for a constructive approach to the issues
discussed," Putin said Russia is interested in developing long-
term healthy relations and fruitful cooperation with Poland and
the meeting will do away with the obstacles in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced," he said, "that relations between Russia and
Poland will be raised to a qualitatively new level."
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski, for his part, said Warsaw hopes for new political
dialogue with Moscow, describing his current visit to Russia as "a
chance to open a new chapter in Russian-Polish relations."
</P>
<P>
The talks with the Russian president and other officials were "
constructive and well-meaning, and were filled with confidence
that we must lay a new and solid foundation for cooperation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The ice in our relations is breaking up," hailed Kwasniewski.
"We must avoid things that are damaging our relations and move
ahead."
</P>
<P>
He said it is important to develop Polish-Russian relations in
the spirit of neighborliness, wishing difficulties in bilateral
relations brought about by recent history will be overcome.
</P>
<P>
Prospects for the development of neighborly Polish-Russian
relations must be shown to the people of the two countries, he
said, noting that it is also necessary to re-establish solid
knowledge of each other's culture.
</P>
<P>
Conferring the Polish awards to a group of Russian Interior
Ministry staffers who set free two Polish women from Chechen
rebels' captivity in Dagestan days ago, Kwasniewski noted the
significance of the humanitarian factor in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the importance of a boost in Polish-Russian
economic relations, expressing confidence in raising annual
bilateral trade to 1.5 billion U.S. dollars "in the light of signs
of improvement in the trade shown in the past few months."
</P>
<P>
He announced that Putin and he mulled the possibility of laying
a gas pipeline from Russia to Europe through Poland and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Russian foreign minister called for an end
to the chill in relations with Poland, hoping the relations
between the two nations will be able "to move from cool to warm."
</P>
<P>
During the visit, also his first trip to Russia as the head of
state, Kwasniewski also addressed a Russian-Polish business forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
