<HEADLINE> Ecuador Exchanges 60 Pct of Currency in Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Ecuador said
Monday that 60 percent of the country's currency has exchanged
into U.S. dollars after adopting America's currency for
circulation in the Latin American country.
</P>
<P>
An exchange rate of 155 million dollars still stands ground, of
which 140 million correspond to bills in sucres and seven million
in coins, said sources in a declaration made known Monday by daily
"The Hour."
</P>
<P>
Fundamental Law for economic transformation anticipates the
dollar adoption as the exchange model and pushes back the sucre to
fractionary operations, whereby coins with a denomination equal to
dollar fractions.
</P>
<P>
In big stores, payment is made in dollars, be they coins or
bills, while in small operations it's kept in sucres and dollars.
</P>
<P>
On January 9, 2000, former President Jamil Mahuad announced the
dollar's adoption as the currency in an attempt to get over
Ecuador's crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
