<DOCNO> XIE20000710.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Credit Rises in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumers borrowed money
freely in May, ringing up the biggest rise in consumer credit
since the beginning of the year, the Federal Reserve said Monday.
</P>
<P>
After seasonally adjusted, total consumer credit increased by
11.8 billion U.S. dollars in May for an annual growth rate of 9.8
percent. That was the largest gain since January, when Americans
increased their borrowing by 15.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Consumer credit in April grew by 8.8 billion dollars, less than
the Fed estimated one month ago. That translates into an annual
growth rate of 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
In May, the total amount of nonrevolving credit, such as loans
for new cars, vacations and other big-ticket items, rose 7.1
billion dollars at an annual rate of 10.5 percent, also the
biggest increase since January. That was up from 2.3 billion
dollars and a 3.4 percent rate in April.
</P>
<P>
Demand for revolving credit, such as that used for credit cards,
rose 4.6 billion dollars or at an 8.9 percent annual rate in May.
That was down from 6.5 billion dollars and a 12.7 percent rate in
April.
</P>
<P>
The Fed has raised interest rates six times over the last year
to slow the economy and keep inflation from escalating. The Fed's
rate increases are designed to raise borrowing costs and thus cool
demand for such big purchases as cars and homes.
</P>
<P>
Recent economic reports, however, indicate the U.S. economy is
slowing. Retail sales in May were sluggish, and the employment
report for June showed that businesses added fewer jobs during the
month than expected.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said such data could persuade the central bank
to leave interest rates unchanged at its next meeting on August 22,
just as it did at the June meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
