<HEADLINE> Greece, Macedonia Sign Military Cooperation Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Macedonia signed here
Monday a military cooperation agreement as part of efforts to
improve the relations between the two Balkan neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos and his visiting Macedonian counterpart, Nikola
Klusev, with the aim of developing border forces, mainly on the
Albanian borders as well as cooperation between Greece and
Macedonia within the defense industry.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, both ministers agreed to increase the
effectiveness of their forces on the two countries' borders with
Albania to avoid new dangers posed for them by illegal immigration,
drug trafficking and international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed opposition to any irredentist intervention
aimed at changing the existing borders of Balkan countries.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos reiterated Greece's supports for Macedonia's
efforts to join the European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
On his part, Klusev expressed his wish to resolve the question
of Macedonia's name within this year, which has been the main
obstacle for the improvement of relations between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Macedonia have been at odds since
1991 when the latter gained independence from the former
Yugoslavia in 1991. Greece has opposed the use by Skopje of the
name "Macedonia," which Athens said implies the neighboring
country's territorial claim to one of its northern province with
the same name as Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the two countries have taken some steps to
better their strained relations by expanding trade ties and the
strengthening of cooperation in combating drug and immigrant
trafficking as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
