<HEADLINE> Russia Slams Latvian Court's Ruling on Soviet Veteran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry on
Monday denounced a Latvian court's ruling to sentence Yevgeny
Savenko, an old former Soviet veteran, to two years in jail, as "
flagrantly inhumane."
</P>
<P>
Savenko, an 87-year-old ethnic Russian and a disabled veteran
of the World War-II, was sentenced to two years in prison Last
Friday by the Liepaja city court on charge of involving in a "
genocide of the Latvian people" in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The Latvian court ruling on the Savenko case is equivalent to a
death penalty, the Russian Foreign Ministry said in a statement,
calling the sentence "a big inhumanity."
</P>
<P>
"In civilized countries, judges take into account the age and
health of defendants," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
However, the Latvian authorities, "despite all declarations
about the independence of their judicial system, have yet again
demonstrated partiality in administering justice."
</P>
<P>
Savenko's trial clearly demonstrates "a political order by
circles which would like to take revenge for the past by engaging
in the moral persecution of veterans of the anti-Hitler resistance,
" it said.
</P>
<P>
"The attitude assumed by top Latvian officials, who contributed
to creating an atmosphere of intolerance towards the veterans of
the Great Patriotic War, has played a significant role in giving
an accusative bias to the Savenko trial," the Foreign Ministry
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
