<HEADLINE> U.S. RNC to Focus on Education, Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Education, Social Security and
the need for an inclusive party will be the major issues of the
upcoming U.S. Republican National Convention, organizers of the
conference said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Ours will be a different kind of convention for a different
kind of Republican," convention co-chairman Andrew Card said.
</P>
<P>
"We will be talking about issues like education and Social
Security, which have not been center stage at Republican
conventions before," Card told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Republican National Convention is scheduled to be held in
Philadelphia from July 31 to August 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
Republican presumptive presidential nominee will speak on
Thursday night to project a different image of the Republicans to
the nation.
</P>
<P>
Card said some speakers at the convention will "compare and
contrast" Bush's policies with those of Vice President Al Gore,
the likely Democratic nominee, but they will not attack Democratic
policies.
</P>
<P>
The convention slogan is "Renewing America's Purpose ...
Together" and each of the four nights will highlight a different
theme.
</P>
<P>
Laura Bush, Bush's wife, and retired General Colin Powell will
speak on Monday on the theme of opportunity and proposals for
improving education and health care.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's theme is focused on strength and security, including
a discussion of restoring military morale and readiness. Speakers
include Bush foreign policy adviser Condoleezza Rice and Arizona
Senator John McCain.
</P>
<P>
The vice presidential nominee will speak on Wednesday night on
America's prosperity and retirement security.  
</P>
