<HEADLINE> Colombia's Exports Grow 23.3 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's exports in the first
five months of this year reached 5.151 billion U.S. dollars, 23.3
percent over 1999's same period of 4.176 billion dollars, the
National Administrative Department of Statistics reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The source said that traditional exports (petroleum, coffee,
coal and ferro-nickel) meant 53.4 percent of the total of sales
abroad, that is, 2.752 billion dollars, with a growth of 34.1
percent in value and of 5.4 percent in volume in the period
January-May 2000 over the similar lapse in 1999.
</P>
<P>
These exports' increase is mainly attributed to the rise of
international prices of petroleum and nickel and the growth of
coal sales' volume.
</P>
<P>
Hydrocarburate exports in the period mentioned went up by 63.9
percent from 1.151 billion to 1.903 billion dollars, although in
volume they went down by 20.53 percent.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, coffee sales abroad fell 30.02 percent in value
and 32.51 percent in volume. This means a fall of five percentage
points when going from 13.63 percent of the total of exports in
the period January to May 1999 to 7.73 percent in year 2000's
similar lapse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
