<HEADLINE> Russia's Putin Signs Decree to Raise Pensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
signed a decree Monday to raise the average monthly pension of all
retired population by 125 rubles (4.5 U.S. dollars) to 882 rubles
(31.5 dollars) since August 1.
</P>
<P>
The president made this announcement at a working meeting with
senior cabinet ministers Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The increase will benefit 18 million people and require an
additional 18 billion rubles (642.9 million dollars) from the
government budget in 2000 alone, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
After the decree comes into effect, the monthly income of the
retirees will surpass the law-set minimum living standard -- 851
rubles (30.4 dollars). Moreover, the average monthly pension will
be raised again in 2001, the president pledged.
</P>
<P>
Putin has tasked the cabinet with the fulfillment of the decree.
</P>
<P>
The goal is "to make the lives of ordinary Russian citizens
better and safer, and improve their quality," he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
