<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Unblocks 55m Dollars in Aid to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Monday
unblocked 55 million U.S. dollars in economic aid to Russia that
had been held up since last December due to concerns over the
situation in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The unblocking was agreed upon by EU foreign ministers who met
for their two-day general affairs council at which several EU
member states urged the freeing up of the economic aid to
demonstrate the union's willingness to build ties with Russia's
newly-elected President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued after Monday's council meeting,
the EU foreign ministers called on the Russian president to make
good on his government's commitment to economic and political
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that a priority of EU-Russia cooperation
would be to support "a modern economy that benefits the whole of
the Russian society."
</P>
<P>
The unblocked aid is part of the EU's special aid program for
Russia and the program is known as the TACIS. The 15-nation bloc
has funneled around 4 billion dollars to Russia since the program
went underway in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Hubert Vedrine, French foreign minister whose country has just
taken over the six-month rotating EU presidency, said that the
council would ask the European Commission and the council of EU
economy ministers to pinpoint areas for continued EU-Russian
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers said that the council had recognized
with interest the programs of political and economic reforms
launched by Russian President Putin.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation should be organized for the benefit of the
rule of law and democratization for the sake of the entire society
of the country," said the written statement issued after the
council meeting, the first chaired by France that took over from
Portugal the EU presidency on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers agreed that the next scheduled EU-
Russia summit would be of special importance in that it would be
focused on a long-term, effective cooperation program between the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation bloc is meeting Russia on October 30 in Paris for
the planned summit.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers also instructed the European
Commission, the executive body of the European Union, to re-launch
the preparation of the TACIS aid program for Russia for the period
between now and 2003, especially a proposition for an action
program for the year 2000 with the aim of supporting the ongoing
political and economic reforms in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
