<HEADLINE> UNESCO Urges Search for Fairness in Information Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Organization for Education, Science and Culture (UNESCO) urged
here Monday the establishment of strategies to allow a free access
to information with fairness.
</P>
<P>
Technologies and information must be patrimony of humanity,
said Sofia Leticia Morales, executive secretary of the Mexican
Commission of Cooperation to UNESCO, when attending the
International Meeting of UNESCO Chairs in Communication in Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
On her part, the president of the Latin American Parliament,
Beatriz Paredes Rangel, said that before a globalized world, the
challenge of nations is to allow a fair access to
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The participants agreed that education is the element that will
allow society to accede to technologic innovations and with this,
to make information public.
</P>
<P>
This international reunion, organized by UNESCO with the
participation of over 60 universities and higher education
institutions all over the world, was inaugurated Monday at Ibero-
American University in Mexico City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
