<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camdessus Asks for IMF Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Former International Monetary
Fund (IMF) director Michel Camdessus requested here Monday further
reforms in the organism in order to face in better conditions
challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has upheld all sorts of reforms in the world without
applying modification of itself, Camdessus said at a press
conference in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
This organism has acted frequently as "fireman" of national
crises and left aside its role as the world financial architect,
said the director of the Center for Prospective Studies and
International Information (CEPI) from France.
</P>
<P>
"During my stay (of 13 years) at the foundation I pressed for
changes that have given their first results. Nevertheless, they've
been insufficient," Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
"The task has not been finished, but it's progressing. The IMF
is at the center of these changes, wherefore it's necessary to go
quicker," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "we cannot let ourselves be taken over by present
world euphoria. It's time to start changes within the IMF and not
await the next world economic crisis to present itself."
</P>
<P>
According to Camdessus, the IMF requires new agile credit
mechanisms for nations affected by external instability and
liberalizing of capital accounts in an orderly manner.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus who on February 14 left the IMF post, proposed that
the Group of Seven industrialized countries listen to the rest of
other nations searching for joint solutions to global problems,
such as poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
